the best! my favorite professor on campus, they dont get most engagin and energetic than sheffield if you dont like him, you're not a hard worker and WRONG
No Comments
Rick Sheffield is a god. He cares immensely about students and subject matter, and happens to be damn smart. I loved his class
he assigns a lot of reading that while perhaps interesting has nothing to do with class or exams.  Your grade is based on 2 take-home exams which are a **** if you have oth erstuff going on.
Worst class at kenyon!  Learned absolutely nothing, spent two classes talking about how policmen eat doughnuts, and had pointless tedius takehome exams.
Very energetic and witty, has fun with his classes. A little hard to approach, but still provides a great class.
terrible. over-simplifies complicated subjects. talks to you like you were eight
too freaking energetic at 9am!

I absolutely loved Comprehending Music Performance with H. He's extremely enthusiastic about the course. In general, he's a caring professor. He realizes not all students care about his class, but he'll always match your effort to help you get the grade you want. The textbook is online and written by him, which is cool (and free!). 100% recommend
Genuinely caring, very nice, very knowledgeable. Solid prof.

Heuchemer, though somewhat disorganized, does a really good job at teaching his class. He encourages participation in his lectures (to the point that he would quite often go off on a tangentbut an interesting tangent at that!), and his tests/quizzes are not difficult if you put in the effort. He is incredibly knowledgeablegood for office hours!

Easily one of the best teachers I've had at Kenyon. He possesses great knowledge and anything he can't answer he is willing to look up and discover. The only annoying part is his citation format for his essays, but he is a very fair grader. Would definitely recommend.

Heuchemer does a good job teaching an intro class.  He provides his own written textbook which was free of cost and written well enough that I had no issues with the course material.  His class is not the easiest class in the world but certainly not that difficult.

Probably my least favorite professor I've ever had.  I took Comprehending Music Performance and the class was nothing like its description.  Lectures are boring, tests include nothing that he actually taught, and his textbook is ridiculously long and self-centered.  Never at his office hours and doesn't care about his students.

H. Is absolutely the best professor I've ever had at Kenyon. I'm a bio major, so I didn't know what to expect from his class, but he makes it great. Incredibly enthusiastic, funny, and extremely helpful (even gives you his cell# so you can text him questions). He's remarkably well-versed, and can answer pretty much any question you can think of.

Not bad.  He really knows his stuff, and tries to make class interesting through very dynamic teaching.  He's really arrogant and sometimes tends to ramble in class, which kind of makes you feel like he's wasting your time, but I generally enjoyed the class.

Surprised to read the negative comments. H is hilarious and very dynamic--an excellent combination for a conductor. His sense of humor might be brusque, but the man is brilliant. I'm quite a terrible musician, but he was benevolent enough to humor me and let me play in wind ensemble without complaint. Certainly will miss him.

I was in symphonic wind ensemble for 2.5 of the three years I was at kenyon, I spent my junior year abroad.  I actually ended up quitting because H did not make the experience fun anymore.  I started to feel he was biased against me and gradually began to felt picked on in class.  I don't think he is a good professor.
He's funny, and was rather helpful towards me. But can be cold at times.

simply put: he's a pompous jerk. a friend of mine got on his bad side. i sit next to this kid, and am guilty by association. bam. wouldn't give me the time of day. it was childish. frankly, i'm surprised this guy has a job at kenyon. he should be relegated to a cc.

Re: favorites -- yes, he does have favorites. These are likely to be the people who work hard and have an earnest manner. If you are one of these people, good for you - if not, watch out. Anyone who says he doesn't have favorites is one. :)
He's my favorite professor.  His lectures are amazing.  He should do those Teaching Company tapes.  H is hilarious.  You really learn in his classes.

Awesome professor!  Does not play favorites, just likes hard workers, BIG DIFFERENCE.  Will totally help you rethink history, media, and what you hear day-in & day-out, IF YOU LET HIM.  Just listen to him, he's smarter than you are.
The man is not only brilliant, but scathingly hilarious. Regarding claims of favoritism: Yeah, don't be a moron and he won't regard you as one.
get on his good side and stay there. so much fun if he likes you. fun in class too.

I've taken 3 classes with the man. His class is exciting - H is charismatic and engaging. Outside of class is a different story: He plays favorites like no one's business and is cold and condescending. Take his class but beware.
Great fun and a wonderful person.  Very caring.
A great teacher, but pure evil. If you ever end up on his bad side, you need to avoid him like the plague.
No Comments
No Comments

Can come off as seeming cold, but a lot of this is just that he will not tolerate bull-****. He is opinionated, but he will never grade you off for having your own point of view, as long as you can support it. One of the funniest people I know.
Great professor, great guy, made Music history somewhat interesting.
he's hilarious and a great teacher.
He is completely biased about specific recordings and refuses to listen to students. RUN AWAY
Good teacher.  Yes, a little opinionated.  If he likes you, your psyched.
He's a great guy. Loves dogs. I'm just kind of sick of playing run-throughs.
H is great.  Takes conducting seriously, keeps your attention.
h is awsome :)
H is a great guy and a very enthusiastic teacher. He makes 810's bearable.
heuch is a good teacher, but kind of a jerk outside of class

He does a solid job of explaining the philosophers you read and in making class entertaining. The readings were well selected. Isn't flexible on assignments if you're late on something its usually a 0. Does make facts up about things not relating to philosophy to explain philosophy which I don't mind but some do.
He is such a nice guy. Very good teacher as well. The is a tough course. Be aware of pop midterms and the final is super hardcore.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment: Joel Richiemer was the best professor that I have ever had. He introduced me to a new way of thinking about the world. He is a true teacher, the ultimate intellectual, and such a wise person. With all his knowledge and wisdom, it's unbelievable how down-to-earth, nice & available he is. I will always treasure the time I spent learning from him.
If I could be anyone, it would be Joel.

One of the most brilliant professors at Kenyon. I randomly decided to take his Ancient Philosophy class and years later I still think this course was the best one I took in college. He is so animated, he makes everything exciting- which is amazing for a topic that is thousands of years old. He will make you think!!

Joel is the smartest person that I probably have ever come in contact with. He presents such difficult concepts so clearly, and literally knows everything. He could easily be in multiple departments at Kenyon. Every day I leave class, I feel like my world has been shattered. TAKE HIS CLASSES

Had Richeimer for several courses. Smart, funny, immensely helpful, strangely dressed. Fairly demanding, though soft around the edges. His paper comments are especially thorough--I just wish he assigned more papers! Symbolic Logic was a lot of fun, as was Epistemology. Go to office hours and talk about robots/Quine/Sellars/Japan.

Joel is perfect. My favorite professor at Kenyon. Well, he lets students blather on about philosophy about which they know nothing. But other than that, one of the most interesting and engaging people I've ever known. TAKE HIS COURSES. Grading might be tough, but you just have to review your notes.

Not an easy professor; loves to give pop quizzes and tests. Lectures can be interesting or awful, depending on the day. Likes to ramble on. Plays favorites, especially with Phil majors. Class required a great deal of work, but 80% of the total points came in the last two weeks. Hard grader, gives lots of negative points for wrong answers.
Best philosophy professor at Kenyon. Very engaging, smart and teaching is his life. What else could you ask for?
I want to be Joel Richeimer when I grow up.

symbolic logic required a lot of work, however i always looked forward to his class. he kept me awake for early morning classes with his humor, he's random but a very funny man. the hardest part were pop midterms and quizzes. just make sure you go over your notes and work.
brilliant and hilarious. he can be hard, but he is passionate, and i always looked forward to his class. one of the best professor's at kenyon!!
Animated, funny, consistantly rude (in a good way) -- Joel's one of the best professors at Kenyon. He keeps you on the edge of your seat. Check out his fan club on Facebook!
The man is brilliant, and crazy. His lectures were intense and discussions with him were always candid and lively. One of Kenyon's most animated and interactive professors.

Are you serious? The only reason you wouldn't understand symbolic is if you're absolutely retarded. The man is not only amazingly kind and one of the most brilliant teachers on campus, he is also ridiculously patient. That might be the only problem with him: he is too patient with people  Take him!
Amazing teacher. Extremely interesting. Always funny. One of my best decisions at Kenyon was to take this class.
Listening to Joel lecture is liking getting hit with a fire hose (in a good way). Excellent if you can keep up. He's my favorite professor here.
joel is amazing.  really amazing.  he makes extremely dense material seem lucid.  and he's funny as anything.  quizzes are hard.  will talk to you if you talk to him.
Remarkable
Wonderful, wonderful man. Passionate about the material, friendly, loves to chat outside of class. Classes are fun, mind-blowing, and full of curses.
No Comments
Symbolic logic wasn't hard, it was his inability to actually teach before you turn in the graded assignments that made it horrid. Has a tendency to have class pets.
Teaches cool material, nicest guy you'll ever meet, funny as hell, great teacher
No Comments
one of the best profs here, hands down.
a great teacher
Unclear, blows you off when you try to get help from him, biased twoards some students. My worst classes have been with him.
The best.
No Comments
No Comments
He's a bit hectic at times, but extremely lucid in his presentation of the facts

Yeah, he's getting up there and can ramble a bit but Klein is great. Loves the material and up for a beer with students at the VI. One of those classes thats more about learning from the man than the material. A good experience
Klein is a great man and professor. That is all that needs to be said.
He's been clocked out for a while and is, by now, essentially a living fossil. Surprisingly harsh when it comes to grading. Rewards and encourages simple-mindedness.

I took two English courses this year with Professor Klein and loved every class. say what you will about the man, but I went from a B- on my first paper to an A on the last few, and that's all thanks to him. I am a much better writer now, and at the end of the day, isn't that all that matters?

He promises the class As, so take him if you're just trying to fulfill diversification requirements/want a GPA boost. You'll be bored, and he may humiliate you in front of your classmates/make weird remarks about attractiveness of his former students, but at least you'd get an A.

Klein is such a nice guy, but he's incredibly opinionated - he rambles on and on about who knows what. He promised all of his students all A's as long as they did all the assignments and all of the readings. It's an easy class, but you almost feel bad that it's so damn easy.

A very sweet man, but really needs to retire. He is kind and honestly interested in his students, but the class lacks direction, challenging material or useful feedback. Your time would best be spend in a different English course, most likely ANY other.

A nice guy, but honestly, an awful teacher.  He probably is brilliant, and may have been a great teacher years ago, but is now incomprehensible.  He rambles from subject to subject, then continues to ask questions that make no sense; our class often sits in silence until someone asks what the hell he is talking about.  Our grades are always late.

Any of my high school English teachers would teach this class better than Professor Klein.  He is completely incomprehensible and uninspiring - my class was usually silent.  He gives almost no feedback on papers, and when he does it's very vague and sometimes even rude.  He is stuck in a rut and refuses to have an open mind about literature.

Fantastic professor if you are willing to discuss the reading in class and understand his sense of humor.  A little vague on paper topics, but usually pretty generous when it comes to grading.  He's always helpful, you just have to be willing to ask him the questions.  He really appreciates good writing when he sees it.
needs to retire.
WHAT A TERRIBLE PROFESSOR. Doesn't know what he wants. Never prepares for class. It's high time for him to retire.
WORST professor at Kenyon. Doesn't even prepare for class, doesn't know what he wants from you. USELESS. Avoid at all costs.

This man is ridiculous.  He talks constantly and incomprehensibly about the University of Chicago, a slew of self-aggrandizing stories, etc.  Totally random grader--his paper topics make no sense, and he contradicts himself constantly when he describes what kind of paper he wants you to write.  Made me afraid to be an English major.

Klein is senile so you could just have fun listening to him ramble and say crazy things. He was, however,  the worst professor I've ever had. He is incredibly vague about paper topics, contradicts himself non-stop, and will never be satisfied with your writing. He caused me to have a terrifying 4 month long writers block.

I took this clown for Stories and Story Tellers...he actually called me ugly on one of my papers.  An incredibly two-faced, arrogant professor who needs to realize that just because he went to the University of Chicago doesn't mean that we want to hear about it daily.
an professor who is both interested in what he is teaching and interesting in class!
annoyingly vague about paper topics, loves to hear himself talk

challenges students to look at stories from a perspective they may not be used to adopting, cares greatly for his students- willing to give as much time and assistance as they need, has a great sense of humor.

Worth taking just for his stories about Kenyon and deer sh**.  Our class was really close, we were all stage crew in H.S. and had read the chronicles of narnia.  Quite a group, we even had a party with klein at the end of the year.  I couldn't imagine anyone making Anglo-Saxon so much fun or interesting.  You should take this class.

Prof. Klein began teaching this course because I wanted to learn the language. Assignments are, I'll admit, sometimes cryptic, and he does make the occasional cringe-worthy joke. If this is the worst you get from a professor, you're lucky or delusional. He would kill for his students. A great man.
No Comments
Very tangential. If that doesn't bother you, take the class, and ask him to tell you about the guy who jumped out of Leonard.

Klein is a strange and wondrous bird. His class wasn't very difficult but was very interesting. He wants his students to leave understanding something and if you go to him during office hours he is more than helpful. Nice guy who knows his****. Hit his history of the English Language class, etc.
Very confusing and hard grader.  The class is interesting, but he is way over the head of most people in the class.  Very few comments on papers, you don't really know what he wants on papers.
No Comments

I'll give him this: he loves to talk.  If you find his assignments cryptic and difficult, they are.  He is helpful if you put in the time with him  If you spend enough time talking to him on your own you can boil down the hours into a clear enough topic.
Amazing professor, often misunderstood.

His forays into sexual jokes seem to be an attempt to temper his incredible arrogance.  I wish he would have spent as much time on grading, which is often reduced to very little commentary or helpful suggestions, just a grade. I doubt he reads the assignm

Great Professor. Entertaining, helpful. To the people who dont like him go in and meet with him and he'll help you as much as humanly possible. Great to talk to about literature. Completely fostered my interest in Modern Short Story. Easily among the best
No Comments

his enthusiasm for the subject matter is palpable and his knowledge unquestionable.  Yet Klein's presentation of the material is muddled and the class often feels directionless.  One of his colleagues aptly described him as  past his prime.
This guys nuts.
Cryptic. Has been quoted saying,  I'm not sure what I'm looking for in this assignment... but this definitely isn't it. C.

brilliant, obscure, baffling, a man only understood retrospectively, let his enthusiasm be contagious, learn how to write short reader responses from him if you want to do anything in life-- it may seem impossible, but it will be invaluable. love his car
Unclear instructions, hard/unfair grading.  Told the same story about a girl in a car at least 6 times!
i thought reading aloud ended in grade school?
Kinda tricky, very available for extra help, but once you get it it's a snap
brilliant guy, sometimes talks too much about his own opinions
makes absolutely no sense
always available to grant assistance, and his classes are invigorating!
Way too nice, cryptic with instructions, but knows his stuff.
No Comments
On a personal level is fun, but I have no respect for him as a professor.
amazing but need to be on your toes and if you zone out for 2 seconds that will come to haunt you

Prof Camerra-Rowe is a truly great professor and her class is indispensable, but she makes you work for it. A's and praise are not common, but getting one from her means twice as much as any other professor. Get ready to read, pay attention, and give your all, and you will be rewarded with true growth, knowledge, and skills.

Professor Camerra-Rowe is easily one of the most intelligent, well spoken, and kind professors I encountered in my time at Kenyon. She does not set the bar low for her students because she knows they all have incredible potential to learn and grow in her course(s). Her class lent me new perspective on many issues and shaped my college experience.
ratingTags: Respected--Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: One of my biggest role models.  She is so smart, cares about the subject like no professor I've ever seen, and probably won't give you an A.  Modern Democracies was my favorite class at Kenyon because of her and I was a math major. Just the best.

Energetic, brilliant, inspiring and challenging. She taught me how to approach difficult readings, and how to write excellent papers. She expects a lot from students because she knows all their potential. I have no complains about her. If you're looking for an easy A, go home. If you want to learn a lot, her class is the right place.
Pam Cam is the best! Had her for two classes. Very challenging, but the best prof I've had at Kenyon. Worth the work!

Perhaps the most enthusiastic professor I've ever encountered. She learns everyone's name within the first week and seems genuinely concerned with each student's learning. That being said, she is a very very difficult grader (of the "'C' is average" camp), but does seem to round up a little in the end. TAKE A CLASS WITH HER!!!
awesome prof. Nice, energetic and interesting. make sure to pay attention and not be annoying, particularly on a bad day.
ouch! she's so sarcastic.  watch this one.

Amazing!!  Very popular amongst students and not hard to understand why.  Challenging, but worth it ~ engaged, brilliant and entertaining.  I was very suprised to read a comment sayin she's rude~she responds to everyone's comments with respect and enthusiasm.  Her class really is an experience you don't wanna miss.

This was an awesome class! I loved how open and engaging Professor Camerra-Rowe was. She was always avaliable, both inside and outside of class. Even though it was hard, it was definitely worth it. Take this class -- it's the greatest!
Not sure if she's still teaching this....And yes, her voice is a little grating....But lighten up, people!  She's a good professor.

Her voice is the most annoying noise I have ever heard in my entire life.  Every time I hear her talk I want to blow my head off with a shotgun.  She gets really excited about stupid boring/obvious stuff, and then her voice gets really annoying. Damn, I hate that class.

She's friendly sometimes, but other times just crazy and kind of rude and inconsiderate. Clearly knows her stuff, but doesn't always explain it very well. Also, I'm normally not one to complain about the workload for a course, but she seems to forget that we're taking courses in addition to hers.
fab.  love it
ok
No Comments
Professor Camerra-Rowe is an excellent professor. She sets high standards, not only for her students, but also for herself. Intelligent, funny, and entertaining.
No Comments

i can't think of a single aspect in which pam-cam could be a better teacher.  regularly meets with students for *hours* outside of class.  unbelievably engaging, brilliant, and caring.  establishes an amazing repor with classes.  wants you to succeed.
She is amazing, one of the top three teachers in the school.  Her work at Kenyon has made the PSCI department a more well rounded and stronger department.
awful.
She's the reason I came to this school. One of the best Kenyon has to offer.
one of kc's absolute best: brilliant, charismatic, caring.  simply incredible
No Comments
awesome lecturer, very caring, quite crass
funny as all hell

I understand that Professor Elliott is something of an institution at Kenyon, but I found him to be well past his prime. I respect him, and he is VERY knowledgable and full of interesting anecdotes, but lecture was all over the place and I never understood where my grades were coming from, even though I managed to do well enough. Frustrating.

A professor who I am sure to think of as i go through life. Liberal Democracy in America is the most important class I ever took at Kenyon, the books we read and the issues we covered made me a better democratic citizen. That's all in large part thanks to Professor Elliot. He is sweet, genuinely curious and razor-sharp smart. A Kenyon great.

One of the great professors of an incredibly good department. Lectures are crystal clear, logical, sometimes humorous, and contain a combination of theory and policy, data, etc. His grading for papers is extensive and fair, and his transitions lenses and suits are sharp. He would make a great dictator (as he likes to joke abt). Take him if you can
the man knows his stuff. he's been at kenyon forever. classes are all lectures, with only a few papers and a final for the class. if you take notes everyday you'll be set for the paper topics

Professor Elliot is a solid professor. His lectures are clear and follow a logical path. He is known for choosing great books for his courses. While he takes a long time to return papers, he is a fair grader(read: relatively easy compared to the rest of the PSCI department). Take him if you get the chance.

Very, very nice and one of the best dressers at Kenyon. He certainly knows his stuff, and puts a great deal of care into correcting papers. I just happened to hate all of the paper topics. Still, good professor.
Really great guy.  Despite having been there forever and having tenure a hundred times over he still takes the time to type up suggestions for every paper written.
Hrmmmmmmmm.... Elliott is a complete legend. Rambles and is completely scattered but is very intelligent and funny.

Always available to help out and seems genuinely interested in his students. Can be a bit scattered and unclear in lectures. Does a good job of keeping his personal biases out of the class. I got a lot out of his class.

A little disorganized at times, but overall very good.  Contrary to what a previous poster said, I found that he did a very good job of keeping his personal politics out of the class (and yes, I am a liberal).
No Comments
Hilarious. A little scattered at times, but absolutely hilarious and very smart. He knows his stuff.

he is politically conservative and his lectures and grading style forwardly reflect this.  be wary.  also, his style attempts to lead you to predestined answers: if you attempt to create a new (however supported) theory, you'll be shot down.  he is smart.
with a voice that weird, he could be a LOT more interesting. squeak!
hard as all get out in a weird weird way.  overrated but still has it in him...

Almost all of this discussion-based class has been nearly a lecture. He asks questions but he does not tolerate any opinion that he does not agree with. He doesn't get political, but he also avoids any criticism of the texts, and even though we only get to the surface level meaning of a text, I am ending the semester barely understanding anything.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Professor Spiekerman is a breath of fresh air in a department that desperately needs it (at least on the political philosophy side of things). I disliked Prof Leibowitz in Classical Quest--he is certainly a smart guy, but reptilian in his classroom demeanor. Modern Quest with Spiekerman was fun and I felt that I got much more from the texts.

Definitely a very boring class. He loves the sound of his own voice and does not attend to or respect his students' opinions or thoughts. Not a mean guy, just drags on lectures and does not do a good job of engaging with his students.

Dry, boring, and dull are the three best words to describe this class. Spiekerman can't lead a class discussion to save his life, shows very little sympathy for his students, and he wont entertain a point that he doesn't agree with. The pop quizs are on the most minute details and aren't helpful. This class was the biggest waste of my time.

I'll agree that he wasn't an expert at class discussion, but I loved his dry wit and his ability to push ideas that I didn't hear from other sources.  Plus, he's one of the few professors I had who really loved his students.

Terrific teacher.  Engaging and funny; incredibly smart.  He is the type of professor that epitomizes Kenyon learning.  You will remember him long after your days at Kenyon, and it's likely he will remember you.

I heard a lot of negative things about him coming into the class, so I wasn't expecting much, but I was pleasantly surprised. He's definitely got a sarcastic edge to him but I think it's a good thing. He leads good discussions and can argue either side  of any debate. He is undoubtedly conservative, which might explain some of his unpopularity.
Sarcastic and cynical.. but in a good way. Not a particularly hard grader in my experience. Gave good comments on papers and was very helpful in office hours.

I generally like my teachers hard and sarcastic, so I assumed I would LOVE him.  Not true.  He viewed texts narrowly and had no idea how to lead a good discussion.  I truly wish I had taken this course with a different professor.
Smart and Sarcastic. Occasionally class discussions can take awhile to progress, but usually very interesting and delivers great lectures. Honest, thorough feedback on papers.
Doesn't read into the text too much in Quest for Justice and relates everything to life. Other classes may be different.  Very interesting discussions!
He'll challenge you. Make sure you do the reading. Not the best for Quest; doesn't really know how to conduct discussion, which is unfortunate.

A very sarcastic man who grows on you through out the year. Leads very interesting discussions that hold your attention easily. As a grader he is tough, but very satisfying. Write a bad paper and he'll let you know. Write a good paper and he'll pat you on the back.
Generates engaging, balanced discussion in class.  Pays close attention to improving students' writing style in addition to their conceptual grasp.

Spiekerman can come of as arrogant, but once you get to know him he's a great guy.  Can sometimes jump to conclusions and is sometimes easily angered but has an incredible mind.  But he loves his students, and you'll still talk to him years afterward.
Pompous and arrogant, provides no justification for his opinions and grades with expectations well above those of college freshmen. Avoid at all costs.
No Comments
No Comments

Spiekerman rocks. He's sarcastic and sometimes even shocking, but he's a genius, and seems to really care about his students and their intellectual growth. You grow to love the  uh s and  riiiight s. Plus, he's hot.
Smart enough that he can maintain the drinking schedule of his students.  Fun, whip-smart and engaging.
No Comments
If you have a sense of humor, you'll like him.
Funny guy...definitely not warm and cuddly, but not too bad.
Worst teacher ever--should be fired from Kenyon.
Not overly friendly, OVERLY sarcastic, and sometimes rude.
Also choice comments in IPHS.  Very amusing, nice guy.
Genuinely cares about students and the material he is teaching.  Puts a lot of thought and effort into his lesson plans.  Incredibly nice human being.

Here's the thing: probably the nicest guy ever.  My favorite professor to talk to/visit in his office.  Completely hilarious.  He's also extremely intelligent and has some really interesting ideas.  Classes, though, aren't always well-organized and you're often left confused as to what's going on.  That said, a lot of good comes through in the end

Professor Gebhardt makes the material interesting.  He has a sense of humor and a love of teaching.  He is late to class often.  He is very quirky, so it takes time to get used to his idiosyncrasies.  But you can excuse his quirks because he is who he is, and that's a good teacher and a good human being.

Gebhardt is the cutest person in the world and he makes class really fun.  I wish I could put him in my pocket and carry him with me wherever I go and listen to all his hilarious comments.  He made the material of the class interesting and I learned a lot.
Knows how to keep students interested in studying an obtuse language all the while making sure that his students do well. Also, he's a great guy.
He's wonderful.  Absolutely wonderful.  Great teacher, great human being.  case closed.
Gebhardt is the best. Kenyon would be considerably diminished without him!
He's awesome.  Can't think of any complaints.

Okay, so here's the thing.  Gebhardt is a major link in the old Kenyon gossip-mill.  No matter what he says to your face, you can bet that he is talking about you to other people, and it won't be nice.  He may be enthusiastic, but that is negated by his total lack of organization, as well as his tendency to stab his students in the back.
Great guy and a fun, enthusiastic prof. My accent was so much better after taking a course with him! I would definitely recommend his courses to anyone really interested in German.

I love the Gebhardt. He's funny, nice, and very helpful. I didn't think his class was very hard, so I asked for extra work and he gave it and was willing to meet during office hours and correct it. He just got tenured this year (04-05), so hit his classes up.

He is awful.  Does not stay on topic.  Rambles on about everything, except for the ridiculous required reading.  He grades unfairly and gives final grades arbitrarily, not based on grades/performance throughout the semester.  He sucks.
Explains well and is always willing to help outside of class.
He is a horrible teacher.
Gebhardt is very knowedgeable, and interesting to learn from!!
Gebhardt's passion for his students and profession are shown from the beginning.
A hard worker who can be confusing but certainly knows his stuff.
The one boil on my Kenyon experience.  This woman was the worst--best thing they ever did was get rid of her.
The *single* worst professor/class experience I had at Kenyon.  Irrational, talentless, cold.

A horrible teacher.  She hates anyone smarter than she is, meaning that she only liked 1 student in the class and was pretty nasty to everyone else.  Projects her own religious views (very Christian) on other religions we study.  Cannot lead a discussion.
a bad teacher in too many ways to list
Has no idea how to lead a discussion
nice lady, can be long winded
horrible, just horrible... I don't want to talk about it
After having her for three classes, I should have learned my lesson.
No Comments
One of the best teachers I have had at Kenyon.

Prof Hartlaub clearly cares about his students and valued the class's opinions on how the course should go. While he wasn't the most effective communicator in class, he was available out of class and rewarded hard work. If you're interested in the content and willing to work hard, I'd take him as a professor.

comment: Brad seems obsessed with the idea of his class being difficult, and more than just a distribution requirement filler for a lot of students, which is strange because its and intro-level stats class about SPORTS. He also just does not teach the material in class. It's astounding. I had to teach myself basically everything in this course.
Very fast during his lectures, hard to understand. But he is very kind and helpful in office hours.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Very helpful.  Fun to be in class with and took time to help students through work no matter what.  Great teacher.

A generally good professor who needs to find a far better textbook and/or teach out of it less.  Helpful, but the work is sometimes outrageous (if not always hard).  Tests are extremely difficult.

He's a good guy; I'd love to go have a beer with him, but taking his class is a different issue. Their may not be a more difficult teacher at Kenyon. There's no way to get an A or A- in upper level math classes with him unless you're a crazy math obsessed workaholic. Nice guy though.
He refuses to teach. Classes consist of us doing exercises. Professors aren't paid to be task masters, but teachers. Obviously he didn't get the memo.

I hate math, but I love Brad. If you ask for help, he goes out of his way to make sure you understand what's going on, and he is always willing to listen to student feedback about the pace of the class, etc. He's definetly one of my favorite professors at Kenyon. I wish I was better at math so that I could keep taking his classes. Seriously.
Extremely hard... not worth taking if your just trying to get your QR.

Amazing. Extremely funny and genuinely cares about her students. She demands a lot, but she's always willing to help you in anyway she can. Take Russian and you'll have a mentor and friend for life.

I can't even begin to describe how great Prof. Olshanskaya is. I took intro Russian with her on a whim and now I'm a major. Absolutely loves her students and is really fun in class. Very caring. My entire intro class, minus one person, continued to the second year with her, which says a lot.

I would recommend prof. Olshanskaya's classes to anyone interested in taking Russian. She is a wonderful teacher and mentor. Both approachable and helpful. Has a great sense of humor - not for anyone that is too uptight to take a joke. So many of her students go on to do great things and gain great proficiency in Russian.
Olshanskaya is the reason for my success in Russian studies. I would be nowhere without her. The best professor and advisor I've ever had and probably ever will have.
She is my absolute favorite person on earth; not only is she a great teacher, she really cares about her students.

Nicest professor at Kenyon. Genuinely interested in her students, you feel like you got a new mom (without all the scolding). Throws Russian parties with yummy food, shows Russian movies w/Papa John's. Loves everybody. Really funny too.
I've never even had a class with the lady and she's like the nicest person in the world.
My favorite teacher here. Can be blunt at times, but dont let that fool you--its just part of russian culture and it probably means she likes you.
mother russia. intelligent, kind, and a great sense of humor

THere is nothing not to love. She is the nicest woman alive. She is understanding, flexible and puts in however much time you ask for. She genuinely cares about her students, sends them home when sick. She treats everyone like her favorite student.
If we were not seperated by age and language, I would marry this woman. SHe is truly a great professor.
is genuinely nice. 'motherly' is definitely the right word.

A truly phenomenal professor, I don't think I have a single criticism. Seductions was the best class I've ever had in my life. I recommend Sergei to everyone.

Probably born to be a professor. Make of that what you will. But seriously, this guy knows what he's doing. His ability to lead a discussion is extraordinary, and he does his best to make the material as interesting as possible. He's also super organized and returns everything in a timely manner. Plus, he's sexy in the kind of middle-aged dad way.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment: Seductions with him was one of my favorite classes I've taken my first semester of freshmen year. I cannot imagine a better man. Class was so engaging and all the movie screenings were super fun, not to mention the creative options for each paper and rewrites offered. Honestly, everyone does pretty much well if you just put ! in ! the ! work !!!

Sergei deserves his reputation. He handled a difficult class with ease, making some difficult texts and projects approachable and inspirational in time. He's a brilliant lecturer, and his persona tied the class together. I've recommended him to everyone.

Sergei is great. He is great at facilitating conversation and offers rewrites on all of your essays in case you don't do as well as you hoped. I enjoyed going to class and hearing what he would ask. Never made your comments feel wrong and fostered a really great learning environment. Highly recommend.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: So passionate. Sergei made me want to do nothing more than analyze literature for the rest of time, and I don't even like critical theory. He is one of those aggressively smart people who never talks down to you. This class was a joy, but incredibly demanding, time-wise. Over-prepare whenever possible. Not doing the reading = certain death.
Take every class he offers. Smartest professor I've ever had. Demands a lot, but class is never boring.
Is there anything in the world he doesn't know? He is a well of knowledge. Very organized and passionate about what he teaches. Embodies the best that Kenyon can be.

Sergei's class discussions are always fun if you come to class prepared. If you don't do the reading, you will have nothing to contribute and will be bored. His comments on papers are frustratingly vague, but he gives generally fair and leniant grades and always offers you the opportunity to revise your paper. I enjoyed my class with him.

A tenured professor who actually CARES about his students? What a novel idea! Sergei is the best English professor at Kenyon, bar none. His classes are fun, engaging and incredibly organized. He encourages students to rewrite their papers and gives tons of helpful feedback.

Very good at leading discussions without dominating them. Provides helpful feedback on papers and, from what I saw, grades fairly. Midway through the semester people got lazy about doing the reading and he called us out on it, which I appreciated. Less willing to tolerate bs comments than other English profs I've had.
Interpret it his way sort of guy. Useless comments on papers. Condescending and disrespectful. Worst professor I've had.
Amazing.  Insightful.  Great professor.  Only contribute as much as you want to contribute to the class.  Does not force you to speak but makes you think introspectively.

His questions can leave you wondering how specific he wants you to be in a response, or if he's asking for opinion or fact. He had us write questions for discussion, but rarely used them. That said, Sergei is a BAMF. He's very kind, and demanding without being absurd. He likes to hear the sound of his own voice, but that's ok, because I do too.

I don't know why everyone is saying that he's a conceited jerk. I personally found him very nice. I thought his paper comments were helpful and detailed. In class he lead discussions without spoon-feeding and encouraged us to answer our own questions. He is also very funny.
Very intelligent, helpful, and clear. Good use of class time. Very hard grader.

No, no, no, no, no! I do not understand how a professor can earn tenure and then live off it for decades. This man embodies everything that's wrong with Kenyon, not the least of which is the fact that all these people still eat out of his hand whenever they can.
Love him! Extraordinarily accessible and very passionate about what he's teaching.
Brilliant and very helpful professor.Take him if you want to learn a lot and/or improve your writing.
Great at leading discussions, brings in material and can tie the plays to current events.  Excellent teacher, but not very helpful as far as papers go.
Very condescending. Can be helpful if you give him a chance.
What a jackass. A real****of the walk type of guy. He must've started working off his reputation years ago.

Kenyon's version of Kenneth Brannagh, but not quite as egotistical. A man who knows his Shakespeare. Will make you see and understand things in the plays that you never would have thought of. Teaches the lesser-known plays, increasing your exposure to the bard. Says quirky, funny things in class.

Very interesting and helpful professor. Brings in a lot of extra information into Shakespeare, relating it to all facets of both the canon and everyday life. Really knows his stuff.  You can rewrite any paper once after it has been graded.
Great, great, great.  He's my advisor, and he is genuinely interested in what you have to say.  Helpful, not a lecturer, knowledgeable, inspiring.  I couldn't ask for more.

comment: Quest for Justice often touches on controversial issues, and if the class doesn't have a bond, it can't tackle the topics. Luckily, Mood is phenomenal at facilitating discussion and getting us all to open up. Incredible professor!

comment: Prof Carson is so sweet and passionate about what he does that it's contagious. Initially, I didn't think I would find subject matter very interesting but his enthusiasm brought it to life. The final was difficult and included extremely specific factual questions pertaining to the readings, but I really enjoyed this class. Def go to office hours

Carson is one of the sweetest and most passionate professor's I've ever had. His voice can be soothing, which may make it hard to stay focused. But if you do, you'll find a committed professor who is very eager about his areas of study. Go to office hours, he'll help with papers and get to know you better, which helps.

Carson is one of the most enthusiastic professors at Kenyon. I wasn't initially interested intaking this class as a prospective English major but he made it so interesting and fun! He tends to keep students about 2/3 minutes past class time because he doesn't wrap things up quickly, which can be a bummer when you have another class to get to.

Carson is such a wonderful man. Loves what he does. If you do the reading and take notes you'll do absolutely fine. Not interested so much in theory/criticism as he is in substance/thematic elements. He's what you see when you picture a liberal arts English professor. Crazy smart underneath the eccentricity.

clearly loves to teach and very enthusiastic. gives detailed comments on essays. the one bad thing, which was kind of a deal breaker for me, was his inability to get class discussions really going, which i think is pretty important in an intro class, especially such a small one

One of the most enthusiastic professors I have ever had! I'm a science person, and this man had me thinking I would love to be an English major. Knows his stuff and cares about his students above all else. His feedback will take your writing to the next level.
He's great!  Helpful, passionate about his subject, and smart.  The class was organized fairly and in a way which made it fun.  He gives good comments on papers.

Carson is amazingly dedicated to his students & clearly engaged in his work. I was an English major not particularly interested in his areas of specialty (the Romantics & the early American novel). However, after my 1yr course with him freshman year, I took another class with him for the writing feedback, bc he gives you so much--changed my writing

Eccentric and kind. He's enthusiastic about the material, like a little kid in a toy store. He wants you to like it as much as he does. He was inspiring and knowledgeable, but he largely depends on class participation and sometimes people are unresponsive. Maybe just watching his movements in class is entertaining enough. Definitely a character.
DELIGHTFUL.

Incredibly dedicated to the students and the material. Excellent theoretical knowledge, though he struggles more with teaching that than the literature. Does his best to get you to like the material, though he doesn't always succeed. Allows you to think in class, unendingly kind.
Very eccentric, but passionate about his subject.

I have never had a class with less interesting discussion -- but I never got the impression Carson wasn't really listening. I was kind of amazed he still was, actually. He's awesome, and his analysis is sound; I just hate Romanticism.
as someone said before, you don't always feel that he's really listening, tends to say 'yeah, yeah' a lot

If you are interested in the class and the subject, he will inspire you.  He knows his stuff, and leads interesting discussions, if you're willing to participate (which, alas, most intro to English people aren't).  This is not high school english, which is what most people expect.

You can learn so much if you just LISTEN to him. The people who complain are the ones who expect English classes to be easy. He will really make you appreciate the history of the novel, as well as theory if you give it a chance. This is what studying literature's all about.

Carson is a gecko. His class was boring, his teaching uninspired, and his tone completely flat. Carson turned me off almost completely to the English department. STEAR CLEAR OF CARSON! He is nothing good.

Very passionate about reading; every comment is personal for him, but he has a great sense of humor about student views, too.  Loves what he does and makes class funny and wonderful.  If you look him in the eye, you might never get free.

Is good for a laugh, due to all his strange affectations and gestures. Can't help but feel he doesn't pay attention to what the students say, likes to put in his 2 cents (or 10 dollars.) Not intimidating.
works hard to make discussion interesting. one of the best teachers i've had.
moves like a dancer, dances with words, stimulates thought

There's a widespread sentiment on campus that Prof Rowe is pompous and callous, but the fact of the matter is that he is smarter than you, and unlike many professors, unwilling to suffer fools. Some of his readings and lectures informed my very conception of the world order. This class was my favorite at Kenyon. Just don't be stupid in class.

Easily my favorite professor thus far at Kenyon, and I'm not even a PSCI major. Loved coming to his class and always found the material and lectures so engaging. Insanely smart and very willing to help you if you come to his office hours. Hope I can take more courses with him in the future!

I'm currently in a graduate psci program and this seminar prepared me for graduate school more than any other class I took at Kenyon. If you try in his classes, they will completely change how you think about the subject and add in some analytical chops to boot. Really interesting lecturer, and a funny, nice guy with insane intelligence.

I think it was a really interesting class.
 Rowe is kind of a silly man who is very self inflating-
 but thats actually a lot of the fun, I thought

Completely agree with 9/20/04. For those saying "he thinks he is smarter than everyone else", here's a fact for you: HE IS. If you have tough skin and seek the people/world-smart and not just book-smart, take every class you can with him. He single-handedly changed my life and my experience at Kenyon.

Prof. Rowe is great in seminar. He is interesting and tells funny stories, but more importantly he asks tough, engaging questions that really make you think about things you take for granted. Excellent teacher.

I hated this class while I was in it. I thought it was pretty boring and pointless. I worked really hard on the policy paper (which is near impossible) and the final and the work paid off. I learned more applicable information in that class than in almost any other. People say Rowe is arrogant and into himself, but he knows what he's talking about.

IR class. arrogant. assigns his own articles and grades you on whether you use his lecture and articles in your papers. probably the least approachable prof i've had.  likes to hear himself talk.  brilliant but oppressive as a teaacher.
a bit likes to hear himself drone on, but even he can't spoil the class. works at not totally looking down on us.

Rowe is a brilliant man, and it shows in his lectures.  A lot of reading for the course, and the final was a pain to study for, but you learn quite a bit if you try.  I never saw Rowe thrown off by a student question, and he uses wonderful analogies to make abstract points.

Some people love themselves.  Rowe thinks he's God's gift to mankind.  Assigns grades arbitrarily on who he likes or not.  He likes pretty school-girls and is a dirty-hippy hater.  Lectures are okay, but he assigns tons of reading that he never talks about.  For IR take McKeown instead, unless you're a relatively attractive female.

Intelligent, funny, willing to talk outside of class.  Very opinionated, but always willing to listen to others if they can back up their argument.  Go to PSCI lunch table and office hours to really get to know him better.

He may be smart, but you'll never find out unless you go to office hours.  Class is a dumbed-down mess that fails to teach you anything.  I would have learned just as much going through the syllabus on my own.  Got an A, but it was excruciating (not in terms of difficulty, in terms of psychological distress at the though of having to go to class)
i took all the classes that i could that he taught.  i will miss him when i'm gone.

Rowe has a clear intellect and a dry humor.  People who claim he has an agenda have probably been made fun of by him for saying something dumb with no real argument.  His lectures are dry sometimes, but it's nice to have a prof who doesn't at all rely on lame discussions that don't teach anything.

Clearly biased, but unlike what some have said, he seems to be perfectly willing to listen and respond to opposing views. He's also a genius, so even if you don't agree with him, you can get a lot out of listening.

Yes, Professor Rowe is very smart, and a little arrogant because of it.  But hell, if I was that smart, I would be too.  I think his class is very interesting and I really look forward to going to it.  There's a lot of reading, but it can be done.

dont hate the player hate the game. fact is d.rowe is to smart for most of the idiots on this campus who call themselves political science majors. he has no agenda, no unyielding ideology. he is one of the most insightful and thorough thinkers on campus.

About as nice as Bill O'Reilly. Class is dry and boring. Ridiculous assignments, puts others down all the time. "what do these kids know, anyway". cocky.

true, he's all about lectures, but at least they're interesting

his background gives tremendous depth to class discussions

Professor Kohlman is one of the smartest people I've ever met and truly pushes you to go beyond what you think you know. She's hilarious and keeps discussions entertaining. Such a gem take her class

She is very challenging because she expects you to know your stuff. She stays true to her word and is helpful if you seek it. She's intimidating but funny too. If you stay on top of the material and do what she asks, you will be fine.
excellent teacher. love her courses.
Can be intimidating.  Will challenge you.  You will most likely love her or hate her.  Know your stuff; she will call you out on it.  Through it all I learned a lot and enjoyed having her.

She is incapable of teaching the material in class in a clear or meaningful way. Students in her other class seemed to like her, but I was not alone in finding her completely inadequate for SOCY 226. I cannot name a single student in the class who likes her. Do not take classes with her.

She is always late for class, and is a lazy and unhelpful grader and person. While her select teacher's pets all love her, the rest of us are forced to attend to the "Kohlman hour," where she wastes class time on unrelated and pedantic personal anecdotes and fails to teach requisite material (7 students just failed her midterm. 8 students got C's).

She is a powerful and brilliant woman and has been by far the most engaging, interesting professor I've had at Kenyon thus far. She is intimidating, especially in the first few weeks of class, but if you work hard and stay focused during her lectures, you will honestly become inspired to be a better student. She is amazing!

I wish Marla Kohlman were president. That class kicked my ass so hard it went numb for about four months, but I wouldn't have it any other way. One of the best professors I've ever had, hands down. You can tell she used to be a litigator. Think before you speak; don't say dumb stuff, she is absolutely not tolerant of ****, which is refreshing.

Spends 15 minutes on an anecdote and then 3 vaguely relating it to what we're supposed to be learning. Wandering lectures, unclear in what she wants out of assignments. I believe she's intelligent, but this class wouldn't have proven that to me. Haven't learned a thing.

Marla can seem a little crazy at times, but she's actually a really cool person. She's very friendly and clearly wants her students to succeed. She'll work you hard (we read a book a week for this class) and she's a tough grader, but you'll be a lot smarter for it.

Not consistent, was supposed to get one grade and at the end she changed my grade an entire 3 1/2 grades.  So I ask WTF? One of my worse academic experiences at Kenyon, but definitely not the only one
No Comments

Professor Kohlman expected me to do a great deal of work, but was also available whenever I needed to her to help me.  She's extremely dedicated and passionate about teaching.  I would have been worse off had I not taken her class.

Seems pretty hard ass at first but very nice once you get to know her.  Very hard grader who spends most of the class talking about her kids and personal life, and is very strict about deadlines.  All in all though she challenges you to learn a lot, and you do get a lot out of her class.

Oh my God, love her, love her.  A legacy at Kenyon, a person who makes you ten times the student you were.  Tangential, but always with a purpose in sight.  Ignore the unhappy faces, she is dynamite and everyone should take a class with her.

Absolutely wonderful.  I could not have asked for a more enthusiatic, more brilliant teacher.  She's the reason I'm a soc major, and can make a student interested in anything they study with her.  One of the best professors at Kenyon, and my personal favorite.

One of the worst classes I have ever had.  Hugely intimidating.  Not enough lecture or explanation of reading materials, even when students expressed confusion.  Grading all over the place-- had no idea why I got the grades I got.
challenges you to do well. very affective
Auditor only becasue i don't have the time or energy for the class. I love the class, it's interesting adn very helpful.
This class was team taught with Jan Thomas, and thank God.
you either love her or hate her...but it's worth it to find out.

I think that she is the only professor that actually make us work hard for our grades. She makes you think about everything and she is intelligent. She knows her **** adn is not afraid to be the only Afican American female professor on campus.

Excellent teacher, brilliant, good at making things make sense.  However, her admirable no-bulls**t attitude is harder to respect because she so blatantly and unapologetically plays favorites.  Suspicious grading, too.
Poor time management.  Lots of attitude.  Probably knows the material, but can't communicate it.  Doesn't listen to students.  Difficult to work with.
Tough, but fair.  Makes you earn your own grade, is willing to listen to students, and is also not here to take students crap.  There should be more Marla Kohlmans

Awesome professor! If you want to take a class that pushes you to actually LEARN, then take one of hers.I learned more in this course than I did all my others put together...all four years of others.Extremely nice on a personal level- does NOT take crap!
opinionated, yes. but knowledgable. tough tough tough.
No Comments

he is soooo boring (yeah I needed 4 o's). This class is this exact same as watching grass grow, seriously to a tee. wanted to be a rslt major until I took his class. I could write all of the things that make his class terrible but I can sum it up by just saying that he is a bad professor. do not take a rslt class with him you have been warned!!!!!!
very nice and helpful outside of class
Good at making people feel like an idiot, which is fine when it isn't you looking stupid in front of the whole class.

Easily the worst professor I have had at Kenyon.  He clearly knows a lot about the subject but cannot get any of it across in a compelling fashion.  I have never hated going to a class more than his.  It is so boring. He is a tough grader who doesnt explain things well enough. I was going to be a RLST major before I took him.

Professor Adler's class, while very easy, is also extremely boring.  There is no deviation in his teaching style.  He seems intimated by his students (especially men) and gets frustrated when nobody responds to his awkwardly posed questions.  The problem is, he can be condescending and even rude to students who speak up in class.  Some like him.
I really liked this guy, it makes it that much better that he's really excited about the material. very nice and very helpful.

Professor Adler may be nice enough, but he's extremely awkward (not in an endearing way), RARELY takes attendance (which makes his class easy to skip), and is insanely BORING. I was interested in religious studies until I took a class with him.

Has the knowledge but can't express it in an interesting/engaging way to his students.  This class puts me to sleep, I think I have ADD now.  But I have perfected the art of doodling!  Paper assignments come out of nowhere.  Easy vocab quizzes.  Relatively easy class but extremely boring.

Subject matter is interesting but he does not hold my interest. Available outside of class but can be condescending and says "I don't know" to a lot of student questions. His lectures are straight from his notes, no deviation from day to day. Not the most engaging prof.
oddly hypnotic
Nice and very helpful. Smart guy.
He's not the most exciting teacher, but he loves his subject matter and has taught me a lot.
This guy has a lot of trouble relating to his students in the class room. He may know a lot, but his class is one of the dullest at Kenyon.
A smart guy, but I think students make him a little nervous.  He sure knows his Japanese Buddhist sects.
knows his stuff, but cant relate it well to students, classes are random tangent talks, helpful outside of class
No Comments

He's not the most knowledgeable in his field (his chinese characters and japanese characters are often wrong) but he tries to be a good teacher.  His teaching style is reminiscent of a highschool teacher
No Comments
Great person to talk to out of class.  Has trouble engaging students in class discussions, but shows interest in the field and in Kenyon.
Sucks.  I havent learned anything all year and I'm getting my worst grade in his class.
woody allen but without the art. somehow made chinese rel. boring.
wise beyond his years
No Comments
Favors discussion, open-minded, wise
Easy and bumbling, a fast A

When he says "If you want an A, do this" do whatever that thing is. Very good professor with great lectures. Straightforward with what he wants. I found the writing element of class to be counter-intuitive personally, but his class is worth taking.
The grading...who knows? Otherwise Scott is a nice guy. He's constantly telling jokes, and he might pick fun at you a bit, but he's a good professor. There's hardly any work in his intro classes.

Professor Scott may be the best professor I've had for a seminar while at Kenyon. He's got a rather interesting style. Anything you say in the first half hour of class if likely to be wrong, even if it's right, but the back and forth between students and Scott weaves a clever stream that usually leads to an interesting conclusion.
I though Professor Scott was amazing.  He gave detailed lectures that were more like listening to a story than a lesson.  He sparked my commitment to history.
great
great if you like lecture classes. very funny, nice guy.

i love professor scott. best professor/teacher ive ever had.  hard to realize it while your sitting through a lecture at 10 in the morning but if you care and you want to be there and you like learning about the south you will love him, give him a chance the lectures might put you to sleep but hes passionate and incredibly funny- take this class.
good stuff

Boring lectures that consist of him reading off a paper for 1 hour glancing up every now and then to make an irrelevent (sometimes funny) joke. Great guy outside the classroom however his lectures are unbearable. Oh, and he is an easy grader.
I want to have an affair with Prof. Scott. He's amazing. His lectures are long but I could stare at him for hours. His only downside is that he's married. I'm working on that...
Great classes.  Almost all lecture.  Great sense of humor, very nice guy.
He's a good lecturer and is very amusing. The man has a great understanding of the South.
I decided to become a teacher because Prof. Scott.
At first this class is great but listening to his lectures makes you want to kill yourself after a week.
funny but not very helpful and the way he reads his lectures is a waste of class time
great
easy

Hour-long, read lectures... no class discussion... extraordinarily immature outside of class. Easy grader though, and amusing when he looks up from his notes. His lectures are fascinating- great material.

The man, through and through. Funny, personable, tons of integrity, and definitely knows his stuff. Should have been a character in O Brother Where Art Thou. Very adept at mantaining a balance between a fun classroom atmosphere and a serious course.
Great teacher, great klecturer.  does have prepared lecture each class, but definately can ad-lib too.  funny guy, and a pleasure to wake up early for.
Amazing

Scott is hilarious, thought very un-PC.  If for no other reason, I show up to class b/c it is funny.  Though he reads his lectures, he gets them just right and presents the info in a very receivable way.  This is a fun class.
He is hilarious, knowledgeable and one of the best Professors Kenyon has to offer.
not interesting. reads a prepared lecture to the class. good guy, but so boring
Absolutely invigorating professor, and extremely helpful
so funny and really helpful outside of class

yeah!!!
Sarcastic, but knows her stuff. A good professor. WILL call you out for being late.

Dunnell is a great historian but her teaching is somewhat lacking.    The group discussions felt forced and overdrawn.  Her lectures felt out of order, in that, I had trouble understanding a clear chronology of events.  The quizzes were sometimes hard and sometimes easy.  Overall, the subject was cool but the class felt kinda boring.

This class was a decent amount of work but it was definitely worth it! I learned a lot about the subject and the seminars themselves were both informative and engaging. There were a lot of papers but the feedback was excellent and she was available during office hours. Professor Dunnell was approachable and very knowledgeable on the topic.

This class has a lot of assignments and readings, and I wanted to drop the class many times through the semester, but because I love her and the subject so much I didn't. She is extremely funny and caring (she'd bring oranges and chocolates every class, we spent the last class watching Mulan). I love her tremendously and I learnt so much from class

Dunnell knows her subject really well and I find the combination of lecture/discussion in her class engaging and enjoyable.  One of the few professors here who I'm intimidated by because she regularly laughs students off the stage.  she's not always as clear as she thinks she is, and something treats students like they're stupid.

I don't understand all these negative reviews. I'm really interested in East Asian history, so when I saw that Professor Dunnell had lower reviews I was disappointed but decided to take a class anyway. It was great! She's very friendly and conversational, and likes to laughdefinitely not mean-spirited!

Dunnell is a decent professor.  She uses an interesting mix of lectures, textbooks, and types of assignments, and she's very smart.  I don't know exactly what it is that makes her students apparently uninterested in her lectures.  She tends to be almost mean in class, talking to students in a surprisingly sarcastic way.  She means well, though.
Good teacher, very smart, interesting personal life. Not a very good lecturist and discussions sometimes become awkward, but on the whole I'd recommend her.

I've taken five different history classes at Kenyon, with five different professors. Dunnell is by far the worst. She's boring, her lectures are God-awful, she has no sense of humor and is altogether just a mean-spirited person. If you can, avoid taking a class with her.
Willing to help, however if it is not her way it is wrong, and her lectures are incredibly boring.
Her imperial china class is great, but I would caution against taking an upper level seminar with her: she's not good at leading discussions.
excellent

Ruth is a really sweet woman and I have alot of affection for her, but sometimes I think perhaps she is thinking on a much different plane than most of her students.  If you take her for what she is (an incredibly smart woman with some slight yet endearing eccentricities), you'll get along just fine.
Her lectures are the most convulted things I've ever heard. It's impossible to follow what she's talking about.
She's very helpful, but all the class is mostly all lectures.  It can get rather boring.  But it's not a hard class at all.
She's friendly enough, but frequently confusing in both lectures and assignments.  She knows her stuff, but has trouble conveying it.
Not always the clearest...easy for intro classes, but not as much for upper level.

nice woman, but has problems with lecturing.  the reading and lectures are terrible uncohesinve, and the reading volume in doable.
Flakey as anything, but an easy grader, and nice
