Prof. Van Holde is the best professor I've had so far. He's passionate and knowledgeable, and it really shows in class, lectures, and office hours. Readings are a must- the seminar class is fully based on discussion. He asks hard discussion and test questions, but grades pretty easy if you know your stuff. I learned so much from this class!

One of the passionate professors I have come across, and it is well reflected in his engaging approach to lectures.  He is clearly very knowledgeable and presented us with a fascinating selection of readings.
He'll challenge you, but what a gem. SUCH an engaging prof; he really makes the readings come to life and class time fly by. Best class I've taken at Kenyon.
Passionate about the subject matter and really cares about his students. I wish every professor was as good as him.
My favorite professor at Kenyon, took both sophomore seminar and senior seminar and loved them both.
great teacher! my favorite at kenyon so far.

Took him his first year at Kenyon (I graduated in '91).  He was great.  Still remember his class (and the books on the reading list) today.  Since then I've lived alot in Asia (particularly China), and still remember what his class taught me about the revolution and Chinese society.  Glad he's still at Kenyon and doing well.
I want to be him.
Steve is great! Explains everything thoroughly. Has a real passion for what he teaches. Writes excellent comments on papers that really help for the next paper. The best prof I've had at Kenyon.
very good
Great but needlessly anal.

One of the best prof's Ill EVER have. Not to mention really attractive- and the fanny pack! But above all else, extremely passionate about his studies and invigorating. Will make an informed environmentalist out of anyone! Simply put- sheer excellence.
Great lecturer and discussion leader.  Very hard grader.
Hands down the best professor I had at Kenyon. I highly recommend!
Brilliant
a bit strung out but quite interesting

I love this man. Often you hear complaints from students that a professor is a kind and funny person, but unfortunately a terrible professor. I'm happy to admit Professor Matz fulfills both criteria; he is extensively knowledgeable about literary theory, Modernism, and books in general -- while being a caring and easy-going guy. Take his class.

Very discussion based (obviously), so mileage will vary based on class, but overall a fantastic professor. A few reading choices weren't fun (Robinson Crusoe) but their purpose was clear. Offers clear feedback and is unafraid of telling you when you're off-track (a good thing). Clearly loves his subject, which often translates to rest of the class.

Professor Matz is the most incredible professor.  Everyone that doesn't have a class with him wants to because he's so unbelievably intelligent.  I took his Writing the Mind course which including a lot more reading and writing than the rest of the 103 English courses, but it was completely worth it.
Great professor. I took 'Writing the Mind' with him, and while the material was only sometimes interesting, his passion always was.
Great great great.
Only person I know who can turn a comment that's totally goofy into something absolutely brilliant.  Plus, he can be just oh so silly.  Matz is a God!
Kind, charismatic, encouraging, and incredibly intelligent. He makes you feel comfortable in discussion but also isn't afraid to tell the class how it is. Best English teacher I've ever had.

One on one, he's great. But sometimes makes fun of students he thinks are asking obvious or stupid questions. Obviously knows his stuff, but if you don't have something ground-breaking to contribute to discussion, check yourself before you raise your hand.
He's friendly and really interested in talking to students.  Just use a lot of technical terms in papers and you'll be fine

One of my favorite professors. I liked Modernism before his class, and now I'm helplessly in love with it. I want to marry it. Has an incredible reading list--Ulysses drove me insane, but he made me appreciate it. Fair grader and very helpful. I can't wait until he gets back from Exeter.

amazing prof and one of the best graders on campus.  even better, crafts incredible reading lists.  can give a great lecture but, yes it's true, allows way too many idiots to spew their crap theories all over the rest of the class.
I studied 20th Century Brit Lit under him before he left Harvard for Kenyon; he's one of the very best English profs I had in college.  I can't imagine that he doesn't still rock.

If he can have his morning smoothy he's great, but when his blender pitcher shatters watch out.  When his classes start off with a discernable topic they are some of the best at Kenyon.  Just let him start you off with a Dolly Parton story and your set.
Wonderful man and sweet as can be, but lets dummies in class take too much time talking crap. Wastes time that he could be saying valuable stuff
Great guy, smart as paint, but needs good students to have a productive class.  Often lets too many idiots speak their mind, but is funny when he indirectly makes fun of them.
Excellent prep for Grad school
He made me love Modernism, which I thouight was impossible. Perfect balance of lecture of discussion. You actually know what you're supposed to get out of the class. Plus he's absolutely adorable!

my arch enemy.  great reading list, strange theory list, he is boring, unsure of himself, and didn't do enough to draw me in-- might have been due to class full of idiots.  mixed bag of obvious brilliance and dull dull dull. he'll benefit from experience.
who claimed class was boring??  i love prof. matz and the class is great
Boring, boring, boring
He's so adorable!  And he has a dog named Monkey!
LOTS of reading &discussion--turns all inane comments into something brilliant
great lectures, contagious enthusiasm, solid professor.

Miriam is so wonderful.  She truly cares about her students and wants to see them succeed.  She assigns interesting assignments as well, varying from photo analyses to writing our own Haggadah commentary to presentations on Modern Judaism.

I started out disliking the class, but I came to appreciate both it and Professor Dean-Otting. At times it felt like her grading was a bit ambiguous/biased, but she really cares about the topic and her students and wants to help them succeed. Her office hours are great: she is very intelligent, kind, and has a lot of fascinating stories.

I cannot recommend Miriam enough. Best professor I've had, no doubt! Her lectures are absolutely insightful and engaging--her passion definitely shows. She clearly cares deeply about her students, and is more than willing to help.  Her course convinced me to change majors. Take her class. You won't regret it.

Her term quizzes are bogus, you can study for hours and still get a C because the information you have to memorize is ambiguous.  Since this is religious studies you would think that writing could have many directions. In reality, you write to a broad topic with a correct answer or get a B- or lower regardless of your vocabulary and organization.
Horrible Experience.

Miriam is interesting: she is intelligent, yet only entertains ideas that she agrees with. I wish she would humor my ideas a little more- if she doesn't like what you have to say she pretty much ignores it. But, she picks EXCELLENT readings that are so intriguing, and she organizes her course very well. She also values student participation!

Unhelpful and judgmental.  Curriculum okay although I took a comprative religion class in high school that was more interesting.  I too had the experience of visiting during office hours and being treated like she was doing me a favor by even entertaining my stupid, silly, sophomoric questions on how to write the type of paper she was looking for.

Miriam is the most welcoming, sweet, calm, lovely woman that I have met at Kenyon. She cares for her students deeply, and wants to personally get to you know. You see her biking around campus and immediately smile. Take her classes, every one of them. She is fair and loves talking outside of class about what you are thinking about. I love her.
She is a warm, caring, smart professor who really wants to get to know you. She knows her stuff and stimulates class discussion. Amazing Religious studies prof.
Wonderful! Super intelligent, knows everything about everything. Very nice, understanding and fair.
An amazing teacher and mother, hands down.
No Comments

Amazing Professor!  She knows her material like the back of her hand, and is still always open to new perspectives from students. Challenges you to really think about the material. Integrates contempory material (such as poetry, music, and news articles ) with texts. Just a fantastic professor!
Knowledeable and friendly. Another great Kenyon prof. who knows everyone by name in a class of 35. Best religion prof. here.
Great professor, greatest class this year, very insightful, brillant woman, won't let you get away with ****, she is very sharp, i highly recommend, she will make you think.  great personality.

Can be either very inspiring or downright nasty. Very indignant about petty things, but there was a definate connection in the class.  I have enjoyed it and would not hesistate to take it again.  She's a good professor.
people love her... don't know why.  she is judgemental as all get out.  ended up dropping her class because she was unapproachable and downright rude at times.  sad story.

Barf!  Am I missing something? She is one of the worst professors I have had. I went during office hours to review a paper and she acted like I wasn't entitled to be there if I was going to ask such asanine questions. Nice teaching!
One of my favorites, i love her class and her approach, highly recommended
i'm going against the grain, but hello?  she's boring!  and basic!
Great professor, and great human being.
A very brilliant man and excellent Professor. Discussion is sometimes strained in class, however, he loves when students visit his office hours. I am sad to see him retire.

Possibly my favorite class at Kenyon and I was a physics major! RB is a delightful prof with a wealth of knowledge. He carefully considers the work of his students as long as it is clear that they've put in the time and effort. Put in a little, get out a lot. Also, world's expert on Cy Young. That's just cool!

great professor, great advisor. warm, inviting, excited about the material and that bleeds over to his students. i love that he's been at kenyon so long, and has been allowed to pursue varied interests. yes, he makes students do reports, but i am interested in teaching and saw that as an opportunity, and the reports gave me access to material for papers and just more expansive topics from the courses. he also allows creativity in coursework turned in, which is very cool
The best lecturer I've ever had and such a nice man.
most overrated prof at kenyon.  most of his classes are nothing but student reports.  avoid this class.
Best Professor Ever.

great professor.  but has too many student reports.  in a three hour seminar typically 2 hours of student reports--which are terrible.  does not lead discussion well.  avoid this class.  only takes classes he lectures in most of the time.

Perhaps the best teacher ever?  He makes every subject so interesting... you'll hardly notice the 3 hour seminar go by.  He LOVES it when you turn in "non-traditional" assignments (web pages, fiction, etc) so have fun!  I wish this man could teach every subject... I'd know and love it all!
I *love* Professor Browning! If you don't take a class with him while at Kenyon, you're missing out something grand!

I want this man to be in the Parliamentary-style debate each year, that's just how good a speaker he is.  Singularly the most brilliant lecturer I've ever heard.  I can still hear him reciting Tennyson verbatim.  Amazing and essential.
Greatest class at Kenyon
A wonderful professor and a wonderful human being. I respect any man who is obviously brilliant, but still takes classes in other areas to challenge himself. Browning personifies Kenyon.
Inspirational and motivating as a teacher and advisor. Easy to talk to whether it be a class matter or not. Became a real mentor to me.
great teacher, by far best history prof at kenyon
No Comments
No Comments
An excellent professor who is fun to listen to and learn from.
Prof. Browning is an amazing teacher; he really knows what he's talking about and he has a passion for the stuff.

Reed Browning is both the moral and intellectual compass of Kenyon college. Brilliant and passionate he is comprable to Woodrow Wilson, moral and intellgient, but with an air of tragedy surrounding him. The Best.
Really nice and helpful. In a class of maybe 35 students, he knows everyone's name. Recites poetry and sings.
A dear little man, but boring and unchallenging.
ooh, browning is brilliant and passionate, funny and an organized lecturer. and everything said below.  but i can't help but feel he's losing his touch a bit...

I was told he was great.  Seemed just okay to me.

Reed is a must take @ Kenyon

Dave's lectures were amazing. Engaging and hilarious, they conveyed the information in a way that was easy to understand. Short-answer and essay exams are only based on lectures and not on readings so if you miss one class it could hurt you. But he's accessible outside of class and gives good explanations of concepts
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--Amazing lectures

comment: Suggs is awesome. Take an upper level with him if you have the opportunity to.  He's not an easy grader, but you'll be okay with that.  He talks a lot but also remembers every word he says. Write down everything, especially his definitions. If you go to office hours he will point blank tell you what is on the test.

Suggs is a really good storyteller. The class itself is pretty boring, but his stories make it more interesting. Incredibly helpful in office hours and his puppy is the best. If you were to take a class in the Anth department, I would suggest Suggs
Suggs is amazing. He made me want to be an Anth minor. He's so thoughtful and intelligent and it was always a joy to go to his class. If you get the chance, take a class with him. It's amazing.

Great professor, great guy. I love to listen to his stories, in class and outside. He's humble yet incredibly smart, and loves being able to inspire his students. Definitely take a class with Suggs before you graduate
Such a cool professor.

Dave is a huge goof who also happens to be a genius.  His lectures are interesting  and his personal anecdotes never fail to entertain.  He loves teaching and when people come into office hours.  Take this class if you want to be entertained and obtain a deep knowledge about the subject.  This is not an easy A, he grades very strictly but fairly.

Anth of Development was a great class, offered a different perspective on development initiatives and allowed for thoughful class discussion. Suggs likes you not to agree with him as long as you can back up your difference of opinion.
The best professor at Kenyon. You'd miss out not taking something with him before graduating.

Human Sexuality and Cuture is an amazing class! His lectures are very interesting and he encourages us to participate, although he likes to talk a lot. Shares lots of (very) personal anecdotes but they alwayd connect with the topic. He loves seeing people in office hours, and he will talk your ear off. Take a class with him. He's so cool.

This guy's so good, I considered changing majors. Straightforward and clear. Peppers his lectures with extremely interesting anecdotes from his anthropology research in Botswana and at Kenyon. One of the best classes I've taken at Kenyon.

Clear, concise and very engaging lecturer. He knows what he's talking about but isn't pompous about it. Always willing to answer questions and meet outside of class. Grades tough, but fair - very clear about what he expects.
AMAZING CLASS AND AMAZING MAN.
two words...love him.
amazing guy...amazing work
Great class lectures, good reading material.  Entertaining class!  You won't fall asleep.  Dave has a good sense of humor.  Grades very, very harshly, though.

Dave's a great lecturer, and while his classes often consist of him talking throughout, he is always ready to be interrupted or to answer questions.  He'll admit that he doesn't know certain things, which is a definite plus. He's also just a cool guy.
best professor i've ever had. keeps students engaged during lectures, understanding, great sense of humor, VERY willing to help out everyone if they go to his office hours before exams. awesome guy!
Sometimes too smart for his students, i think. but definitely a great prof
No Comments
The best professor i've ever had.  I love you dave
as great a professor as he is a person
No Comments
my favorite Kenyon prof. very smart and down-to-earth, makes you want to work.

The best professor I have ever had. I learned more in his class than any other college course, and I was not a history major. Go to his office hours! He is so easy to talk to and has so much insight. If you are lucky enough to take his class, really listen, really engage him in discussion.
Very organized and prepared for class. Office hours are helpful and efficient. He makes class interesting and tells great side stories from time to time. One of my favorite professors.

I love McNair, he is seriously one of the best professors teaching at Kenyon today.  Definitely my favorite of the history courses I've taken.  I took 175 and 176 last year, and he is hard, but fair.  His tests are memorization heavy and he grades mechanics harshly..  His lectures are always interesting, as are his primary source assignments.

I took three or four of prof mcnair's classes during my time at Kenyon. He is amazing! He's a great person and a great professor. He has amazing stories to tell about his careers before he became a teacher. He isn't too hard, but he expects you to do the work. He has clearly laid out guidelines, and it is not too hard to get a good grade.

Early African American History is an amazing class--highly recommended. McNair's style of teaching is what I always wanted from a college professor. Lectures are crystal clear, well organized and often come with a touch of humor. Following his lectures, he takes time for discussions which are always interesting.

Always prepared for class, interesting lectures that are easy to follow. A bit intimidating at first, but very likeable once you get to know him. Sharp dresser, sharp lecturer, sharp in all aspects of his game. I love this guy. In a heterosexual kind of way.

Superficial: Very handsome and wonderful dresser.  I'm a fan of the beret.  Proffesing (hehe): Very interesting.  Sort of wry.  More often than not assigns way too much primary source reading, but the textbook is interesting.  Intimidating at first (he used to be some sort of secret agentish person) but a softie at heart and my facebook friend!

This man is so intelligent, a born professor (tho he has been in the secret service and also a lawyer...) Anyways, P&T was incredible class. If you've ever asked yourself "what is history?", then take it. He's wonderful.
DA BOMB
Great teacher. The coolest guy you'll ever meet. The class is very interesting because it's a mixture of lecture and discussion. Very fair in terms of work load and tests. Such a cool guy.
His class had an inordiante amount of work for an intro class.  Unreasonable expectations.  Also kind of a jerk.

first of all, he is HOT. but, honestly, he is just really fascinating and really helpful. he is very prepared for each lecture and never puts students down. always gives lots of feedback on tests and papers.
Great teacher. Really cool and interesting person. He's really helpful and wants you to get the most out of the class.

I've had multiple classes with McNair, and he's my and he's my advisor. He's a great guy, very friendly and motivated, with a lot of good information to share.  Discussion classes with him are a blast.
No Comments
No Comments

Great teacher.  Communicates well, and makes class interesting.  Is open to all views, and encourages them to be voiced.  VERY good at keeping his political views form comming out.  Great guy, and from Savannah, GA (defneately a plus).
his tests are straight out of High School, pure memorization, but  a lot to memorize sometimes 150 names and events and dates, but memorize all that and get an easy A.
On his game-his perspective alone makes a class with hima  unique experience.  All humanities people should take McNair before graduating.
No Comments
He's a good teacher, and a good guy
definitely smokes. does a good job of making boring stuff relatively interesting
Doesn't require much preparation for class
Love her. She is brilliant and engaged, happy to talk about subject and offer clear help/advice.  High expectations, but brings out the best work you can achieve. I'm so thankful to have had her.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Prof. Dabakis is a powerhouse. You'll be hard-pressed to find an art history professor with a greater range and depth of knowledge--she lectures as engagingly on 18th c American painting as on radical modern movements. Beneath a professional exterior, you'll find stores of warmth and wit for students who share her love of the field.

Took my first art history class with her to fulfill art requirement. Because of that class I decided to become an art history major. She made the material so interesting, bringing the complexity that goes into learning about history and art history into one coherent and manageable whole. No-nonsense. But a warm, bright, professional professor.
Is the ultimate art history professor. Super interdisciplinary in nature, fair, insightful, engaging, funny at times. Super straight-forward and organized. Overall great.

One of Kenyon's most important resources. Refreshingly smart. Gives great lectures, leads discussions into depth (away from the arbitrary comments of art history students. ) She can be quite funny, and is actually warm and understanding. Treats you like an adult and expects you to act like one. Some people shy away from her no-nonsense demeanor.

Absolutely fantastic! Knowledgable and interesting, Professor Dubakis is a great professor. Can seem a bit cold at first, but as soon as you make the effort to go to her office hours, she'll be a friend for life. She convinced me to take an art history minor when I originally had no interest! Can't wait to take another class with her!

What an amazing art history professor! One of the best at Kenyon. She is extremely clear in explaining the historical context of art work and its artistic  importance. She is very clear in what she expects from her her students and is a fair grader. She is very organized, friendly,  and makes art history captivating.

You better love art, because you won't love her. Routinely mispronounces seminal artistic names and locales; doesn't really care if you're interested. No discussion of theory or theme, just pure factual memorization. Snore.

Easily the worst teacher that I have ever had in my entire life.  Grading seemed to be based on how much she likes you. Very stuck up, in fact, I haven't another teacher here who was so stuck up on themselves.  Awful awful awful.
horrible! i had to drop it after a week. definitely not an easy class just to fulfill a requirement. good nap time though.
Absolutely awful. Unless you're an art history major, doesn't care about you. Probably the worst teacher I've had at Kenyon.
No Comments
not good
No Comments
No Comments
Less scary than she seems.  Amazingly passionate about her work, and expects passion from students, too.

Dabakis is one of the few professors at Kenyon who has high standards for her students.  She won't let you get by with BS and that is what sets her apart from other ARHS professors at the school.  Interesting lecturer.
loves anybody who is actually interested and not there to just get credit

I L-O-V-E this man. He can make even the most boring topics seem exciting. He truly changed my perspective on literature and writing in general. He is also one of the most hilarious professors I've had. I would definitely take another class with him.
Lynn is very easy and there is not a lot of graded work. He's a little boring though...
Demands the student to guess his desired response even after repeated rewrites. He made two of my good college friends cry over demeaning advice. Slights grad school. Feels bitter about life.

Worst prof I've had at Kenyon. Wants you to like him but provides you with no reason to do so, unless you count random nuggets of wisdom intended to impress and awe. Even if you go in for help, meetigns are short and useless, and your grade at year's end will be utterly based on his whim.

Very helpful advisor; always willing to meet for coffee or read over papers. Learned a lot from him in Adv. Fiction, although sometimes he wants you to guess what he's thinking, which can be a bit frustrating. Big believer in having as much life experience as possible. Not a huge fan of academia.

A really terrible advisor. Obviously doesn't give a crap. Told a friend to take a year off and travel through Europe, banging every girl he could, before he went to grad school. I thought he was dumb, but I figured out he just doesn't care, and NOT in the praiseworthy way.
Not very helpful. If your story is set in an exotic locale, it's automatically good. Very often out of town (in New York working on Kenyon Review stuff).
Awful.
No Comments

BIG ego.  High expectations.  Although it seems like his rule for good fiction writing is - the more effed up, the better.  Made us grade ourselves together as a class- interesting social experiment, but created much stress.
Brilliant, knows it. Will improve your writing 100% if you have talent to begin with. Suffers no fools.

total jerk. class is entirely tell me what i'm thinking questions, reading length is arbitrary and unrelated to discussion and his assignments are unstructured. he also looks like alf. although i appreciate his hostility towards idiocracy in class.
A wonderful professor and a very talented writer.

He expects a lot, but if u b willing to work will get a lot of of his class, your writting could improve a lot because of him, be willing to work, thought you don't ahve to do every reading like he says you do, just read a couple really well.

She means very well; however, she is super unclear when asking the class to complete assignments (mostly papers and projects). She got very off topic during class and I felt like I learned nothing at the end of the semester. I don't believe she is a hard grader, but because no one had any idea of what was going on, it is easy to get a subpar grade.

I love Laurie. She was my advisor until I declared a major. Took Gender and Cemeteries with her, and while we had posts after every reading, most of our grade rested on a final, collaborative paper. I can't say I learned too much from the class, but I got a good grade. She's so sweet and caring I definitely recommend her!

I really liked WGS 111 with Finke. She's not an easy professor by any means, though. The course's grade is dependent upon paper grades (she doesn't administer exams) and she grades them intensely. However, she wants you to succeed and learn. She is accessible. Clarity isn't her strong suit. She is, however, very smart.

Easiness, Helpfulness, and Clarity are terrible qualities by which to rate Laurie. She is the perfect professor for an interdisciplinary dept. because she knows...everything and really encourages you to consider a subject from every possible angles. I was a feminist before I took Intro to WGS, but she's made me a much more thoughtful, educated one.

Despite my rankings, I actually really like Laurie! She's an interesting professor and class is a lot of fun! Still, she's really not helpful and pretty unclear about what she wants (which hurt my grade considerably). Still, I do recommend you take a class with her!

Laurie Finke is amazing. She's a bit nuts, it's true- she'll often hop from one non sequitur to another, but she's really brilliant. Even if what she's saying is a totally different train of thought, it's still interesting to hear her opinions. She uses a ton of different reading sources, so be ready to read and argue a lot. HIGHLY recommended her!

Didn't always cover reading material, but covered the really essential concepts well by applying them to the films. Has a very scattered style of teaching, but I liked the informality of it. HUGE grammar nazi (quizzes after every paper). She's slightly intimidating, but nice once you approach her. Made me want to be a WGS major (she IS the dept.).

She is a brilliant woman with a lot of insight. However, she wants you to gain the insight yourself without her having to tell you everything. She expects a lot from her students. I've had trouble when I didn't understand something because the connection w
you can't get a good grade unless you have the same viewpoint as finke. her ideas are very fixed- she is certain she is right. if you write as though you had the same view you do well.

Laurie's a bit nutty, and changes the syllabus a lot, but her lectures are some of the best I've heard anywhere (with surprising and insightful illustrations from all over current events, pop culture and literature) and her assignments really brought my thinking to a new level.
No Comments

Laurie can be a super ****, and not very understanding. She will email you if you miss class. A huge grammar nazi-- don't take her classes if you aren't English oriented! I learned a ton from her though...

Super inconsistant, class discussions never oriented to assignments. Finke really likes to hear herself talk and doesn't encourage students to respond or participate. A lot of work that seemed really irrelevant and responses assigned to every chapter read. Don't do it.
Hard on paper grading, has random grammer quizes, and not everything taught was relevant to the subject.
No Comments
No Comments
Probably a fine person, but very opinionated.  Picks favorites and isn't warm to others.

while friendly and interesting as a person, laurie cannot organize a class.  discussions flounder and stray daily.  wildly inconsistent grading, with emphasis on grammar rules which are somewhat arbitrary.  outside of class, great.  inside, think twice.
No Comments
She is so intelligent and I like that she challenges you. very intelligent.
not good for intro, but very interesting in other classes
No Comments
Laurie´s great!  You have to be an independent student though.
lots of work with no relevance to subject.  Annoying
gives lots of busy work but it not difficult, provided you know your grammar!
No Comments
Tomita is awesome. He can be pretty savage in class, so if you're a lazy or slack-off student with thin skin, get ready for a bad time. Otherwise, awesome teacher.
He was rude and condescending.  I really wanted to learn the language but dropped because of him.
Not a fan

This class has been a little disorganized this year as Tomita-sensei experiments with different grading systems, but overall he is organized, an impressively fast grader, and a gentle person. He does his best to help us with our questions, and he clearly puts a lot of effort into the class and is happy when he sees us improving.

It is very clear what is expected in his class. It is one of those classes where if you really care and show effort, Professor Tomita will do everything he can to help you. If you don't then, be prepared for a little cold shoulder.

Definitely the best professor I have met at Kenyon, and such a good person! You learn a lot from his class, and his exams are never hard. You need to study on your own of course, but he is always there to help you.
Great guy, gotta love the man. Incredibly helpful and constantly available, not sure when he goes home. Class is difficult. but not his fault Japanese is crazy hard to learn.

I love Tomita! He's gentle, funny, and encouraging, but he also expects a lot from us. His class is challenging (like any language), but Japanese is fun to learn, so it feels easy. Grading is based on workbook assignments, kanji, reading, writing, and speaking, not on tests, but most study for tests anyway because we don't want to disappoint him.

Tomita Sensai is the best professor I met in Kenyon. He really tries his best to lead students to success, and he is always there to help you. He is really kind and has a quirky sense of humor. It's a must take!

He appreciates effort, that's for certain. His tests are tough, but not impossible. He's so energetic! And he tries to make class as interactive and fun as possible. As a person, he has a funky sense of humor and is a great professor to get to know. I can say with a fair amount of certainty that a majority of my intensive intro class adored him.

As some have already pointed out, he has a difficulty in communicating with his students. Not only because is his English limited but it has a lot to do with his stubborn condescending personality and age. He has been like that for  many years. Why does he change now? This made the class difficult.

Tomita is a Japanese professor in that he expects a lot of effort from you and if you give that, he will like you. He is a difficult grader, but in class he has a lot of energy and likes what he teaches
I had a great time with Tomita-sensei.  I thought he was funny but is definitely culturally Japanese.
Tomita-sensei is truly a wonderful man, and is always willing to help. Strong effort is generally enough to earn a very good grade, so a little work ethic goes a long way.

Uhm...yeah.  Tomita-sensei is very much a "Japanese" professor, which means that if you are willing to give 150% to EVERYTHING you do for him, he'll love you.  If you happen to have a life, or any other interests besides Japanese, good luck (just check out how many people stick with Japanese through Kenyon...that should be a good hint).
Tomita-sensei....well he tries very hard, but his grasp of English is lacking.  It's hard to teach intro Japanese if you don't speak much English to them.
He needs to speak more slowly, for the people who need to process a new language before they understand what's going on.
An absolutely wonderful man, he tries extremely hard but is unclear at times, but overall I have learned so much from him.

Not cool.  Not cool at all.  Mocks you (Handing back quizzes that say things such as  You didn't make it ) and not a fair grader.  Plays favorites.  Also, not to be picky or anything, but I really wish he had a better grasp of English...he's unclear.
Great person, but not a great teacher.  He tries really hard, but just isn't clear in his grammar explanation.  As a grader he's pretty easy.
No Comments
seems to have trouble communicating in English, but is great if you understand
****, sarcastic, can't speak English, makes fun of you

KVA is an amazing professor - she's super engaging and understanding but she also expects a lot from you, and challenges you to think deeper and make broad connections in her classes. One of my favorite classes of all time at Kenyon was with her: the Women in Renaissance and Baroque Art Seminar. Definitely take it if you're an art history major.

KVA is a good professor but not the best one to have for Survey of Art History II. Her focus is on High Renaissance and Baroque so we spend a couple of months on that; that leaves very little time for the last 400 years of material, and so you don't get a great background there. That said, her lectures are absolutely wonderful. She loves her work.

I love KVA. She is an inspirational woman, both as an academic and as a person. She is brilliant and aware, willing to hear what students have to say even if tangential, and so open and supportive in office hours. I was there every other week and she was always happy to see me and help. Couldn't ask for better.

I was in her Survey Part II class and I enjoyed some parts but the majority of my time was spent trying to cram a massive number of works that we barely discussed before the exams. I've heard good things about her upperlevel classes, but her intro is disorganized and only teaches you temporary recall. Also took 3 months to grade a 2 pg paper!!

I hear that KVA is great for upper level classes, but I was disappointed with her Survey II course. She focused heavily on the Renaissance and Baroque (her specialties), after which she scrambled to cover as much post-17th-century art history as possible. The end of the class was incredibly rushed and we never even made it past 1900.

Undoutedly the best Art History teacher I have ever had. She is kind, caring and helpful. Her lectures are precise, her diction and clarity impeccable. If you meet with her in office hours, you will be flabbergasted by her sheer knowledge, and her genuine love of her students.Meeting with her is one of the best ways to improve your writing. Amazing

High Renaissance Art.  A great source of information, gives incredibly thoughtful lectures. Wants the class to participate and contribute.  Reading summaries get kind of annoying. Will talk your ear off at office hours.  Incredibly kind and caring.

Awesome professor. Easily one of the best at Kenyon, hands down. She's passionate,  interesting and encourages you to think critically rather than learn by rote memorization. She also really cares about her students and seeing them do well.

Prof. Van Ausdall is everything a professor should be -- caring, intelligent, demanding, and interesting.  You can tell she really cares about her subject and she does an amazing job of sharing her passion with her students.  If you take good notes in class, you'll do well.  Easily one of the best professors I've ever had.
Very nice woman, but a really tough grader.
Love this woman
so helpful and nice, she has a heart of gold.  makes everything interesting but a demanding grader.
Top notch professor and mentor. Passionate about her studies, terribly intelligent, and a real inspiration. One of Kenyon's best finds to date. I just love her.
she is great!
very helpful
No Comments
No Comments

Professor Clarvoe is exactly what you'd expect a poetry teacher  to look like. She expects a lot out of you, and if you're not willing to give that to her you'll have a hard time in her class, but if you do you will learn A LOT. She's really sweet, an easy grader, and incredibly understanding. Take her class, you'll love her.

Assertive but delicate. She is filled with contagious wonder. Also, so intelligent. I learned to trust her knowledge and passion and accept her guidance. Let her get carried away on rants and listen.  Take her class and go to office hours.

Professor Clarvoe's expectations of you couldn't be less clear. It is one of the most frustrating classes I've ever attended. Her class discussions are incredibly unfulfilling. She gives you annoyingly micromanaging instructions on papers but her expectations still aren't clear. She's a nice person but a terrible teacher.

I ABSOLUTELY love her. Every time she speaks it's like listening to poetry. She really pushes you to learn, engage, & embrace the material. I absolutely hated & wanted nothing to do with poetry before I took her class and now I can't get enough. While she isn't the easiest of graders, her feedback is helpful. You WILL be a better writer bc of it.

Prof Clarvoe is quirky, but in a kind of not so good way.  She's really unclear, and gets angry and makes people cry.  She also takes a really long time handing stuff back.  I think she has good intentions...?  There are a lot of great English professors at this college, but she is not one of them.
She's obviously really smart and passionate about her work, but I had a hard time understanding her.  She is also pretty disorganized.
Prof. Clarvoe's class was one of the best classes I took in Kenyon's English Department.
It is difficult to describe someone who is so vague and yet so precise.  She hits it.  What does she hit?  I don't know, but she nailed it.
I thought the point of small classes was to provoke discussion, but in this class it was more like 12 front row seats in what could have been a big lecture hall.

she's awesome.  as a workshop leader, she's extremely helpful and encouraging, but swift and merciless if necessary.  eccentric speaker, but incredibly articulate and precise.  don't brown-nose.  it won't work.
Really helpful if you ask.  Really knows her stuff and wants you to do well.  I think she is overlooked because she's kind of quiet.
awesome, delighted to be teaching, smart, not too hard.  grew a lot during her class.

She's a genius, and if you listen to her, you will learn. Her lectures can be difficult b/c she's dealing w/ difficult/complicated topics; but what would you expect? She helped my paper writing so much; and she WILL help if you ask. An AMAZING poet too.
No Comments

AS long as you know how to write a coherent paper, hardest part of this class is staying awake.  And don't try to take notes off of the board, your notes will look like an Eng. Dept.'s version of the ink blot test filled with random words and symbols.
kind of spacey
She really knows her poetry, but she certainly keeps her distance from her students.
No Comments

Jens a cool bird.  she's got moxie.  most confusing board notes known to man.  What the frick does four squigglies, seventeen arrows, two stars, and a circle around the word "threshold" even mean?!?!?!  but she's smart and she knows
Lost a WHOLE SET of class essays. Sweet, but dull.
Very helpful, passionate about poetry, taught me to think.

told me she lost my final but still managed to grade it after lost!?!?!&
plays favorites; can be spiteful & unfair to students who work with other poets
one of the best professors i've had
took forever giving back papers. god.
her poetry seminar sucked!
She is so passionate and intelligent

Hahnemman is passionate about her content and her students. She is a tough grader but it always available (and easy) to talk to. She makes the lives of ancient Greeks and Romans relatable. She incorporates modern poetry and theater into her lectures. You need to keep up on the readings to do well on the pop quizzes. My favorite professor at Kenyon.

I LOVE PROFESSOR HAHNEMANN. She is very passionate about the readings, especially the Iliad, and would occasionally tear up in class. While the daily quizzes hurt my grade a little, it's worth it to listen to her thoughtful and inspiring lectures. She's super friendly and approachable, and I highly recommend taking a class with her.

great professor, fascinating lectures, someone who garners respect from her students and makes going to class fun...however, her grading is another story. though not entirely unfair, she is a very harsh grader...be push yourself to work beyond your own capabilities.
Someone called this prof 'very unique'. Well, unique defies degree; but grammar aside, she is actually quite average to me.

I didn't like this course because of the text, but Hahnemann is a great prof. Yes, she's hard and loves to give totally unreasonable assignments, but she has worthwhile things to say. Tough grader; don't expect above a B+ on a paper, but expect to learn something.
Take as many classes as you can with this truly divine woman.
Amazing professor, very kind and insightful. Fairly easy grader for translations, but not at ALL for papers; she will prepare you for graduate work. Overall excellent; take her!

I adore her. She really is the most passionate, earthy, engaging professor I have ever had the pleasure to know. I started with Classic Myth knowing nothing, and she drew me into this phenomenal world, and I have loved it ever since. I adore her.
Intellectually mediocre?  That is a lie.  I spent many hours with her in and out of class and she is not, I repeat NOT, mediocre.
German young lady.  Thinks highly of her clarity, but her vocabulary is quite limited.  Deceitfully sweet, and intellectually mediocre.

A very good teacher. Loves discussion and going into detail. One of the best Kenyon has. A very difficult grader, though (her policy is to drop a paper to a C for a typo, literally), and might get angry if you get an answer wrong. I liked her enough to choose her as my advisor, and would recommend her to anyone.
she is really passionate about what she teaches, and although she demands a lot out of you for assignments, she'll keep your attention and make classes interesting

AMAZING! She is passionate about the material, extremely knowledgable, conducts classes well, gives great lectures (you have to ask for them, though!), and is very creative.  You can't help but love mythology the way she presents it.  Can't say enough good things about her and Classical Mythology!
fascinating lectures! she has a fiery excitement about her field.
She is lovely, brilliant, demanding, insightful, and compassionate.
a really excellent professor.  she knows the classics front and back and will make sure you do too by the end of the course.  a very versatile prof, great lectures.
tricky, very unique understanding of the Classics, so hot!!!!!!
No Comments
Gives VERY unique insight in her lectures.  Has a great lecture voice.
The tests will be based on the lectures, not the reading, so don't waste your time. He is a good lecturer but a little frustrating with returning things and keeping his word.

Really interesting class though some of the lecturers can be boring, McFarlane's were always interesting. Go to office hours, he really appreciates that. Easy to talk to though he can be very intimidating.

While other have given the sense that he doesn't care I can't find that further from the truth. He takes time to help students after class but YOU need to make the effort to see him; he won't coddle you. His classes are tough but he makes you learn the material and tests your knowledge of subject matter.

Almost all powerpoint, but he's interesting and funny in class. However, I do not get a sense he wants to help his students do well. FYI: I had him in INTRO and he used to do all his quizzes open-note and on your own time, but this year the department made him stop. So don't take intro with him, but other classes are fine.

McFarlane's lectures are very good - they always kept my attention and I looked forward to them.  He made the class in general very interesting, and he uses good examples and describes things very clearly.  However, I sometimes got the sense that he doesn't care that much about students, and his tests are VERY poorly written.

mcfarlane is a really cool guy and hes very funny, but his tests are HORRIBLE. the tests are not open note as one of the other comments mentioned, and hes very vague and unclear as to what you need to study for. but he is very smart and knowledgable in his field

He's a really nice guy, and very funny in class, but you don't learn anything because he goes off on tangents every lecture. Also, all the tests are open-note and taken online at your own time, so it's easy to ace the class but again, you don't really learn anything.

he teaches such a fantastic subject area, but his tests are horrible. it's not that they are extremely difficult, it's just that he does not grade them appropriately. it is very frustrating. also, he is never in his office.
Probably not everyone's favorite prof, but I love his classes.

He is a very nice guy, but as others have said do NOT take the class if you care about grades. He is fairly clear in class, but his tests are absolutely terrible. The final grades do not reflect effort at all.
This guy rules

ok. loved the class, except for the fact that his tests were completely ridiculous, poorly written AND he graded them wrong and refused to correct them. yeah. gave us back wrong exams. whoever found him during office hours, hats off to you; he was like the man who wasn't there.

Great in lecture.  I love his classes.  But you should learn not to care about grades, because his tests are the most ridiculous thing you will ever encounter at Kenyon.  Not just hard, but poorly written.
Good luck understanding him, finding him in his office hours, or getting a test back without grading errors.  Other than that, he's a nice guy and knows his stuff.
My favorite teacher!  Such a great guy.

My favorite professor!!!  It's such an awesome class, I always leave completely fascinated.  He's so enthusiastic and the stuff he adds in in lecture really helps make material from a mediocre textbook interesting.  More into the bio aspects of psychology
Didn't need to do the reading, as he rarely talked about it.  Take very good notes though, b/c test material is right from that.  Doesn't get through all the material he intends to.

Do the reading. Take notes. Study. The class is a breeze and McFarlane is entertaining.  Ask questions and discuss because he loves to talk about drugs.
Amazing professor, needs to get the prepubscent boy voice out of the way when lecturing . . . do the work, don't complain, and the As roll in like money

Take his classes.  He may not always be very clear in class, but if you go see him during office hours he is witty, friendly, and DEFINITELY knows his stuff.  I suspect some of the raters gave up too soon... USE OFFICE HOURS and it all becomes clear.
su cabeza está encima de su asno
Very easy.  Everyone who rated him badly here is probably dumb or on drugs.  Get out of Kenyon if you can't handle a class, fools.  You are not babies, welcome to the real world.
He's smart, and wants students to do well, he just knows if you're not reading/paying attention.  And you DO need to READ if you take his classes.  Specially psychopharm, which was good.

do. not. take. physiopsych. incomprehensible, and hewlet kicking out entire classes because they can't elaborate facts doesn't make it any easier.  he's not a bad man, he's just bad at explicating material to students who don't naturally master it.
Terrible.  I can't believe he was hired.
Extremely bright & funny, but a horrible teacher and gives impossible tests.

so funny- and he's clear if you know how to listen

scary kept me on top of my work i like him
Judgmental gossip. Talks trash about students & faculty. Too busy gossiping to teach anything of significance.
Led a very good intro to anth back in the late 80s
The group work got a little old // who likes to be infantalized?  But lovely and so, so smart and worldy.
Good teaching skills. However, very close-minded. Not open to other peoples' interpretations of, particularly, religious aspects.
Awful Professor.  Very difficult to deal with, surprised she got a position in Admin.  Gossips about students.
Very clear, interesting, concise and helpful. The woman is beautiful!!
She is awesome.
with all of the skits, group projects and points deducted for tardiness, it felt like middle school. in fairness, i took her intro class.
Professor Kipp is the best teacher. She's hot
