Focus on group work. A lot of reading, but if you keep on top of it, you'll do just fine.
Rita has shaped my kenyon experience. a class with her is not to be missed.
great teacher loads of fun
How long is her hair when it is down?
I think she grades really hard; she seems to take off big points for the littlest things.

Kluge is definitely a member of the old guard. He's a relic, but an extremely valuable one. He has a talent for critique, and a fascinating past. He's not easy. He can give tough feedback, but it's usually deserved. You know his compliments are sincere. Go to office hours. Listen. He made everyone in my class a much better writer.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: He cares very much about what he does. He can, however, be abrasive at times, and his personality is not for everyone.

There's a difference between constructive criticism and ripping into something. Often times he'll offer criticism for work that isn't very on-point, and he's known for interrupting students and putting his words in their mouths. If you're writing anything that isn't realistic-fiction, get ready for a huge helping of genre-elitism.

He's really not so terrible when you're in intro fic since he thinks the class is a tougher critic than he is- he can be a huge softie- just know when not to push his buttons- ALSO -- DO go to office hours. He is most helpful there.

He has a lot of good things to say and is a smart guy who clearly loves to read and write.  He's also unnecessarily and brutally sarcastic and seems reluctant to help students in office hours.  For all the smart things he says, he doesn't make many comments on stories either.  I wish he were more about learning than intimidation.

7/9 of the books we read had to do with New Jersey and/or masturbation... I wasn't aware that those two things represented the whole of modern American lit.  They guy is a legend because he says he is... he is crass and belittling at worst and creepy/mildly entertaining at best.  P.S.  his base grade for papers is a B.  Come on, so easy...

He favors a bare and realistic writing style, and anything else WILL be criticized to some degree (frustrating). My writing became less ambitious during this course; the best thing I wrote for it was my application paper. ADVICE:: DO NOT BE LATE. The benefits? My classmates, being forced to write, and some comments. The pitfalls? Reread the review.

Kluge expects us all to be writers one day, and will eviscerate your story as if preparing it for publication. I appreciated the level of commitment and investment he showed toward his students' work, but I'll admit the class tends to foster negativity. Don't expect to be coddled. A warning: it's tough to write a 30pg story without midway revision.

Worst teacher I've had at Kenyon. Very intelligent man lets his students run class. Classtime was spent telling everyone how bad their writings were. Kills ambtion and encourages destructive criticism.

Good things: got me to sit down and write a story; saturated me with criticism. Bad things: criticism was mostly destructive; he teaches no method for writing fiction, and thus no means to improve; made my writing less ambitious; made classtime a redundant riff on each student's ineptitude as a writer.

AMAZING. I learned so, SO much. He is amused by his intimidating side, which he employs regularly during class and probably chuckles a lot about later, so know that inside he's kind of a big softy. Get to know him outside of class, you won't regret it.
I am a professor now, and I think this guy was totally overrated!

This class is how college should be. He will make you work like a dog, but you will be glad you did. I came to kenyon for writing and I had no idea what I was doing till I took his class. If you care, and you try, and you are punctual about everything, he will make you into a MUCH better writer. He can also be so scary you pee your pants. Watch out
No Comments
He's a good teacher, but a bit of a jerk.

Wonderful professor; class was always energetic. Some students are frightened by him, but the caustic edge hides his sentimental side. Very in love with his wife, Kenyon College, literature, and his students, in that order. A little self-involved, but always willing to spare time for his students.

I commented here on Kluge several years ago, and looking back now (a few years after gradustion) I think I overrated him as a prof. He is extremely self-absorbed, not terribly perceptive about students/others in general, and needlessly caustic. Difficult doesn't equal good, even in creative writing.

He'll teach you how to write.  If you want to learn, and don't mind getting a B instead of an A, you will learn a lot.  Can be caustic at times, but funny and pretty sweet deep-dwon (ask him about his teddy)
self-centered, certainly.  bitter, just a little.  condescending, oh you have no idea.  but darn it, the man CAN write and will show you how.  if he likes you, that's a gamble you have to take.
If you want to work hard, you have nothing to fear.  Will change your writing for the better.
love-hate relationship with the college in general and students specifically.
his classes are natural high.  contagious.  infatuating.  inspiring.  challanging.  take a class with him before you graduate.

kluge changed my life, flat out. take him if you want to work, if you want to write, if you won't give up and if you are committed to challanging him as much as he challanges you. he cares, trust me. just don't let him know you know.
Definitely has a sexy vibe.  Great teacher. NOT overrated if you commit to involving yourself with the material.
Brilliant, invigorating, one of a kind. NOT a slack-off course-he will PUSH you.
Very self-centered.  Thinks world hasn't treated him like the genius he thinks he is.  Bitter old man syndrom.
most overrated class at the college
too mush polt summary for a college course
No Comments
No Comments
Brilliant man.

Kindest man you'll ever meet, and he's very funny. The class was extremely easy; so easy that most people stopped doing the work by the end of the semester. Not much is expected of you, and he doesn't care if you participate in class discussion. Not a life-changing class, but he is willing to help you and talk to you after class.
What a kind, kind man with such a genuine interest in his students and the subject, but man, could an hour drag.

Royal is one of the kindest, most considerate and understanding professors I've ever had. His office hours are very helpful and his classes keep my attention. I'm taking another class with him next semester!

While Professor Rhodes is soft spoken, he is incredibly patient, very understanding, assigns fascinating reading, remarkably intelligent, and has a very good sense of humor. Very worth taking a course with this man.

Rhodes is AWESOME! The man is the saint of Kenyon College! He listens, incredibly patient, he is the mentor of mentors of mentors of Kenyon College. A little soft spoken and he says idear instead of idea. Beyond that there is not one bad thing about Rhodes.
He's an amazing amazing guy who is willing to work with you oon anything. Able to meet whenever you need. He really does care and has great stories.
No Comments

Royal is a close to GODly.  He is the mentor of all mentors.  Quiet, yes; try sitting in the front row... he is funny as all get out.  He is more responsible for me being a success than anyone else but myself.  Take him and open you mind.
prof. gives interesting lectures, leads entertaining classes/discussions, cares a lot oabout the students and community. willing to meet with students during and outside of office hrs.
He's a sweet, sweet guy, but his voice puts me to sleep. I wish he'd put a little more energy into his lectures.
changed my life.  is the most understanding person I have ever met in my life.
Nicest guy ever, youre gonna wish he was your grandfather.  Has a monotonous voice like the others said, but if you listen you will find him interesting.
Rhodes is great.  He's a wonderfuly sweet man and rediculously smart.  It takes a while to get used to his teaching style, quiet voice and dry sense of humor, but by the end of the class I LOVED him.
he reminds me a lot of milton from office space. If i could just once get him to say where is my stapler, i would cry.
Royal Rhodes rocks!  A humble, brilliant guide to Christianity and the study of religion.

EXELLENT!! I LOVE RHODES! OR ROYAL SHALL I CALL HIM.  HE IS VERY, VERY SCARED OF GETTING SICK SO IF YOU MUST MISS CLASS, JUST SAY  I WAS NOT FEELING WELL  AND HE'LL SEND YOU A 10 PAGE RESPONSE SAYING TO STAY HOME.  GREAT GUY, WORLD RENOUN, QUIET VOICE
No Comments
sweetest slice of humble pie slash encyclopedia on earth.  great voice for dozing.
The most gentle man I've ever met, a brilliant and immensely knowledgeable prof.
he's brilliant and a very interesting lecturer
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments
Interesting lectures, very docile...quite understanding/forgiving. Thumbs up!
brings lots of cool fact/stories into his lectures. a sweet man.
best advisor for french majors
Lots of busy work, but overall a good class.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: She is demanding, compassionate, fair, and really wants her students to learn French. I recommend her to anyone that sincerely wants to learn the language.
She thinks it is fun to demean students.
No Comments
Extremely nice...I really had no problems with the class.  Exams can be a little tough, but the weekly quizzes really helped me stay on top of the new vocabulary we rapidly learned.
Gives unnecessary busy work, but you will improve your French. Impeccable accent for an American.
She is a very intelligent professor, but at the same she can come off as kind of cold.  The workload was overwhelming and not all of the reading she selected particularly interesting.
As difficult and dry as the class was, I really learned a lot.  Knowledgeable, kind-hearted and organized.
Great energy and ethusiasm; very passionate about teaching; cares about students
Not overly nice, but great teacher.  You will learn a lot if you try.
She's not very nice & gets meaner when you don't take another French
not very nice.
No Comments
No Comments
She's very enthusiastic, but her teaching skills are not fantastic. Nice, though
lots of small homework assignments, discussion important
Very helpful, but assumes you're already nearly fluent- tons of worksheets
Has high expectations and is quite vague about what they are. Harsh grader. Not much feedback. Doesn't like personal writing. Often seemed disappointed by the writing produced by most of the class.

I actually wish he was tougher on us in his creative non-fiction class. A lot of terrible writing, and though I don't advocate a prof being mean for the sake of it, it would have been better if he was more blunt. Make use of his office hours because he'll be more in depth and helpful.

Professor Hyde is a genius. Though this class, Confidence Game in America, had some dense and somewhat boring reading material, he brought life to it with interesting lectures that tied everything together in a meaningful way. Tough on papers, challenging exams, but our grades ended up okay. Try your hardest and he's a great teacher.

Class was fun and laid-back, though his feedback and advice were occasionally helpful but often confusing. I also felt a bit shortchanged on my final grade. It was fair but surprising coming from him considering how hands-off he was the whole semester.

An excellent professor. His comments are insightful and clear, he is very funny and jovial in class and he provides his class with interesting assignments. He can be too nice, sometimes, when students' writing is poor. Highly recommended professor.

I personally enjoyed professor hyde a lot this semester. extremely intelligent, makes effort to get to know his students, and makes silly comments in class. I could understand how some are confused by his lectures, many times his knowledge is far above our comprehension.
No. Just...no.
He may be smart (I have no idea because he is never clear) but he treats students poorly and makes them feel dumb.
Kenyon is blessed to have such a genius among them; almost too smart to be a truly effective prof., however.
Brilliant guy, fascinating lecturer, expectations not well defined.
No Comments
brilliant man, very fun in class. one day i want to be that smart.
lectures a lot, which is good b/c he's wicked smart.

Hedeen is an absolutely great professor. She has mastered the balance between being both kind and competent. Very knowledgable and engaging, makes class super interesting and has a great sense of humor. You will learn a lot in her classes. If you put the time and work in, you'll get an A.

One of the best professors Ive had at Kenyon. Cares tremendously about each student and picks up on everyones struggles in class. Would 100% recommend Profesora Hedeen. I was skeptical of language requirements but after a year with Hedeen I cant wait to pursue Spanish further in a post-collegiate setting.
She's amazing!!! Super nice and fun. Very approachable. Hard grader, but if you work hard, you will get a good grade!

Easily my favorite professor at Kenyon!  Definitely take a class with her before you graduate.  She's extremely fair.  If you put in the effort, you'll do well.  Her comments on assignments are super helpful.  My writing improved a lot in her class.  Prof. Hedeen es la mejor.
Professor Hedeen is a great professor.  Her comments are very clear and helpful and she knows so much about what she's teaching.  I highly recommend taking a course by her.
Great professor! The readings are long and challenging but the work is worth it. My Spanish improved tremendously due to class conversation and essay writing.

The most outgoing teacher i've had so far - after our first class she emailed me to say she hoped i'd stay in the class. Some readings were hard, but she was understanding and would go slower or postpone sections if the class got behind. Very good, constructive comments on papers, and a fun professor to talk to during office hours

One of the best professors I have had at Kenyon. She is hard, but appreciates hard workers. If she can tell you are trying she is more than willing to work with you. Funny, caring, and enthusiastic. The class is by no means easy, especially if you haven't taken Spanish, but she makes it okay. One of my favorite parts of freshman year
She wasn't a bad teacher, she just interjects political stuff into her teaching a lot.  Teaching spanish doesn't require lectures on feminism.
I love Kate.  One of the best professors in the department.  You can relate to her in a lot of ways because she is younger and knows the real deal.  Soooo bummed that she is on sabatical this year!
One of the best spanish classes I've taken at kenyon
I learned more in this class than in all of the other Spanish classes I'd taken combined.  She is outstanding.
What an amazing professor. What an amazing class. She is so brilliant and makes you so at ease in class. She gets my A+!

Good conversation practice. Her grammatical explanations are clear, but few and far between. The cultural discussions are extremely repetitive, and the movies are deplorable. Still, it's the best Spanish class I've taken at Kenyon.
Super feminist.  Pretty good teacher.  Grades strangely.
take this class, and there will be no dispute that it is the best spanish course at kenyon
Not a very bright woman, I'd expect more from a decent school.
great teacher, laid back, good sense of humor, very willing to help out, tough compositions, the class is very clear.
I love Kate.  She's an amazing prof. and she is easy to talk to about anything.
A hard class but she's very laid back and makes discussion interesting.  She knows what she's talking about too.
great teacher, annoying class, she makes it 100xs better, fun and friendly
No Comments

AMAZING! Awesome teacher as well as someone who I'd love to be friends with. Kate is honestly, one of the best teachers I've ever come across and sooooo nice. Having class with her is fun and exciting. Kate is just simply and AWESOME person in general.
She's very fun.  The class is pretty easy if you've had Spanish before
Good teacher, hard, fun
She is tough but understanding. Lots of beer jokes in Spanish.

I like Professor Hemkin as a person, and as a professor, but when she was grading our exams she seemed to decide that if you don't remember the exact wording of her 15th sentence of her 12th lecture you don't deserve half the credit for your perfectly correct answer. In short, her grading was frustrating, but I learned a lot from her and her class.

Her lectures were animated, and she is personable and accessible after class and in office hours. Unfortunately she is also frustratingly unfair. Unclear expectations, ridiculously picky grader. Posed vague questions and wanted very specific answers. Would often dock points for not mentioning things she didn't even ask for on exams. Avoid.
very difficult and sometimes confusing during class, but very helpful during office hours

She is really nice and clearly passionate but she is probably one of the most frustrating teachers I've had.  Questions posed are extremely vague, but she's looking for a specific answer.  Takes off unnecessary points constantly.  Treats her class like kindergardeners, but expects PhD quality work.
Easy to listen to and very clear. If you read the book and do the suggested problems then its a breeze and you don't need to pay attention in class at all.

Best chemistry professor.  Wants to see EVERYONE succeed.  Very friendly and talkative.  She is very clear and helpful during office hours.  I found her not to be condescending as some of the other science professors are.

I love her so much!  I have never loved a teacher so much!  She has an AMAZING sense of humor and is super witty and entertaining in our early morning class.  She's a great teacher, if only I could have more professors like Hemkin!
Hard but fair grader. Very nice and enthusiastic. Lectures were very helpful and she did a pretty good job of keeping me awake at 9 am.
She is definitely a tough grader, but fair. She knows what she is talking about and she is always willing to help.
If you want a bad grade, take any class she is offering. She honetly would not mind giving the whole class an "F" if she had the chance.

great lecturer, makes concepts clear and comprehensible. very hard grader...vague as to what she expects on lab reports. class is interesting but near impossible to get an A unless you really ace those lab reports and ridiculous online quizzes (some wks they r easy others they r impossible)
Probably the worst the Kenyon sciences have to offer. Extremely vague and the STRICTEST grader ever! Takes points off for no reason, and gives literally impossible quizzes. Try to avoid.

I had her for intro and again for pchem.  her lectures are simple, but she expects way more (too much more) on exams.  She asks vague questions and wants specific answers.  she doesn't know pchem that well, she constantly made mistakes which made it all that much worse!  and she's very scatterbrained, once slept through our 8 am class.
oh no, oh no

Hempkin gives great lectures.  I studied a lot for her exams, and I would have gotten the correct answer for some short answer question, but because I didn't word it how she wanted to see it, points were taken off.  She is a TOUGH grader!
Worst teacher I have ever had. That made the worst experience of my life. I would NOT reccomend her or any of her classes.
great teacher. demanding, but fair. VERY helpful outside of class.  Go to her office hours.

Okay, she's a bit scatter-brained. But you don't get more enthusiastic. Her tests are REALLY hard -- you have to spend twice as much time on stuff outside of class as you think you do, and just going to lecture is NOT enough to see you through. But she's really helpful one-on one.
Aweful.  Probably the dumbest person at Kenyon.

Fairly accessible.  Good to ask her what kinds of questions to know how to answer that synthesize all that you have learned before a major test.  Extremely energetic in class.  Tests may ask questions that approach the material differently from how she presented it, so must know it inside-out.
She was definitely a little crazy. I remember her tests being hard, but have really come to like her as a person. Would be fun to have for summer science. Energetic and attractive.
so she's wacked out. but really smart. know's her stuff. her tests are ridiculously hard. asks stuff she didn't make all to clear in class. awesome person.

the tests are really hard compared with class.  i learned a lot in class because she made it interesting but i still don't have a good grade.  she's great if you don't mind that or if you're more into conceptual that mathematical stuff.  ps-she's insane.
so much fun!
She teaches like it's high school chem until it's time to take an exam... then watch out! She's GREAT in lab. Go to office hours.
Impossible tests!  Asks really vague questions, but wants specific answers
The class seems to be easy, until the first test!!  She is a very good professor
No Comments

My favorite Kenyon professor. This was my third class with him. His lectures are great and he knows an infinite amount about music history. He's approachable and very easy to talk to in his office which is open most of the time. His tests are hard. His papers involve a lot of research but they're graded kindly with helpful comments.
Ahhh, yes... bach? Bach! Beethoven? mmmm... yes... BACH! - opera?!?! mmmm... (*shakes chalk*) ah! BACH!

Sanders is a very passionate teacher when it comes to music history, specifically Baroque music.  He explains the material well and engages the class with scores and music as opposed to just power point slides.  However, if Baroque/Classical music isn't your interest class can become very dull sometimes.  He grades papers tough but he is fair.

Definitely not what you would expect from a 100-level intro music class. Feels like he's expecting every student to be a music major. He does care about how you do in class however and is helpful, but then again that's not what you want in an intro music class.

Amazing professor, constantly available outside class (I met with him at 7, he arranged class dinners at Peirce, I saw him at every music event I went to). Tests are a lot of memorization but everything he asks for is straightforward and fair. Learned so much, the only class for which I happily woke up at 8:10.
He is without a doubt the best professor at Kenyon College. Not just in the music department but across all departments.

I really like Prof. Sanders. He is an incredibly caring and helpful professor, and his introduction to music history was thorough and well-done. Be prepared to study a lot, though there are no surprises on any of his tests, just a lot of memorization. Also, do the 2-page research papers well in advance. You may think "how bad can it be?" death.

Reggie!!! I love this man- I had him for one class two years ago and he still remembers my name and asks me how I am whenever I see him. Perfect teacher- clear, kind, understanding, knows his stuff, helpful, great at explaining complicated concepts, and has reasonable expectations. And he has the most southing voice in the world!

The hardest working professor I have had. He truly cares about each and every student, and is more than willing to work with you. However, someone has to criticize him: he is more than a pushover, and doesn't have "it" when it comes to intangibles.  You will see what I mean if you take a class with him. That being said, still highly recommended.

Fantastic professor and person. He goes above and beyond and will stay well past his posted office hours if you need extra help. He knows his stuff and will make sure you understand it. His tests and homeworks can be tedious but they really force you to learn. Take a class with him!

Not much to say that hasn't been said. He's a fabulous, ridiculously nice person who knows his stuff really well and has a surprisingly well rounded sense of humor. If you listen in class and take notes you don't even have to buy the textbook. His grading is very fair. Well worth taking any of his classes.

Awesome! Crystal clear lecturer, extremely knowledgeable, tough but fair grader. My only gripe about him (and it's barely a gripe) is that he has a really soothing, chilled-out voice that made me wanted to fall asleep during morning class. Bravo, Professor Sanders!
He's brilliant, he's crystal clear in his lectures, and he's always extremely helpful. His tests are very specific so make sure you take good notes on his lectures and study them well.
Expects a lot of work. Is pretty much the nicest person ever. Seminars can get a bit long.

I cannot say enough wonderful things about Professor Sanders. He is extremely helpful and always available outside of class. He even arranged review sessions before quizzes and exams. He genuinely cares about his students and wants to see them do well. Sanders is incredibly knowledgeable and an all around amazing person.
Absolutely awesome.  Nicest guy I've ever met, and extremely knowledgeable.  Definitely knows his****, and how to teach it.  Take a class with him when he gets back from being on sabbatical.
Professor Sanders is great. You can't have anything but love for him. Watch out for professor Cai though, shes crazy.
very good, but a bit dry for a 9:40. take one of his MWF classes.
really an amazingly nice and caring guy. he is tough but probably the nicest professor around.
Nicest professor i have ever had.  extremely knowledgable
amazing
One of the best profs, I've ever had. Asked him to be my advisor for a reason.
Difficult exams, Amazing guy. Knows the material really well etc
No Comments
Reggie is a great guy and a great teacher. Really cares about the class.
Top notch professor
Very helpful, wonderful professor
Sanders' class is interesting, and he's always accessible.
As long as you kept up with the readings and talked to her when you needed clarification, it wasn't difficult. She truly loves physics and teaching and it shows.
Professor Turner is my favorite professor at Kenyon. She is dedicated to helping her students understand the material, and does so clearly and effectively.

Note that negative comments below are from people in her non-physics majors classes.  She is beloved and valued as a teacher by all the majors and students who aren't just looking (in vain, apparently) for an easy QR.
committed to her students

She is extremely clear and helpful, and knows the material incredibly well. Her ability to explain the material is kickin'. She also has the sweetest halloween costumes ever. She isn't there to make you laugh, she's there to teach you physics.
Not the most stimulating lecturer, but she's really good at explaining the material, and she's more than willing to go out of her way to help you out.

Turner's teaching skills leave much to be desired. Her method of lecture is poorly planned and without direction, and to repeat what others have said, her quizzes (exams in particular) have little to do with the material covered in the class, the homework, and the labs.

Turner is a nice woman. However, she is also one of the most boring professors to ever blight the college. Her lectures are hopelessly convuluted and her tests seem to have no association with the material discussed in class.
this class is easy and she is fun, understanding, and easy to get along with.

While Ms. Turner is a very nice woman, she's a terrible teacher. Not only is she boring as anything in class, she often gets her facts wrong and has to be corrected. Her intro astronomy class is so easy as to be painful.

Ok, here's the deal she wants to see her students do well, she wants to give everyone an A. But beware extremely boring, intro to astronomy you will not learn any of the fun stuff you think u will very boooring tests are very hard, but even if u fail them
No Comments

He is an amazing professor. Lectures are entertaining and fun, he explains complicated topics very simply so anyone can understand them. Very helpful if you come to him with questions and all around great guy. Intro physics seminar is pretty easy, about 4 labs during the semester and homework maybe 3 times outside of class. Very manageable workload

The smartest man on campus - a true genius. An absolutely amazing lecturer, very funny and engaging and a fabulous teacher. He's super helpful in office hours (and during exams!). Don't expect to get any grades back - he'll post solutions, but it's a minor annoyance compared to how enjoyable his courses are.
Professor Schumacher is a great professor, physicists and philosopher!
Prof. Schumacher is amazing. I am NOT a physics/math person, but I love his class. He is super helpful outside of class. You can tell that he is really into what he teaches.
A brilliant man with mountains of personality and a geeky physicist sense of humor. His lectures are very engaging, even for someone who hates science.
Ben is an amazing and concise lecturer, and his passion for the subjects he teaches is highly contagious.
a joy to watch lecturing
A Very good teacher. Take one of his classes even if you're not into the natural sciences.

Schumacher's hero is Einstein, so he gets REALLY into the material, and loves talking about it.  Answers any questions very thoroughly, and makes sure everyone understands everything.  Highly recommended.
Very exciting to listen to, clear and helpful.  He is the smartest person I've met yet.  Strongly recommended!!

Brilliant man. It's amazing he's teaching intro physics. Entertaining lectures cover a lot of material, but it gets across pretty well. Exams are fine if you know the material; he doesn't throw in any curve ****.
Amazingly smart and animated.  He makes class entertaining.
Genius  only rivalled by wife

Peter knows what he is talking about, but his intelligence can be kind of off putting for some. Makes it intimidating to participate in class because I get like he was judging what I was saying. He does maintain interesting class discussions. However, it was unclear until the end of the semester what we were actually being graded on.

I was shocked by how easy this class was.  There was little in the way of rigor, and sometimes the class discussion was downright mind-numbing.  While initially interested in American Studies, I'm heading toward a different major - one that will be more challenging and rewarding.
terrible professor

Peter is a great guy who teaches an interesting class. The material is great, with a lot of movies and guest speakers, and the workload is light. It wasn't my favorite class, but I enjoyed it and don't regret taking it. That said, DO THE JOURNALS.

The best teacher I have ever had in my life. He makes me think in ways I never had before and is constantly pushing everyone to do better.  It's a decent amount of work, but because it's so steady, it's never that overwhelming. Uses films, books, music etc. in a really interesting way to paint a complete picture of the time period.
read howard zinn its better

Rutkoff is brilliant.  He is extremely knowledgeable about the subject matter, and is a fantastic teacher.  That said, he can be strict with his expectations and a bit critical in grading at points.  Also, if you skip class on a consistent basis he seems to take it personally.
Fun! Encourages original thinking.
No Comments
Best teacher I ever had at Kenyon.  Active learning, writing with clarity, orginal thought, learning to read other forms of media....
Amazing

this guy is a nice guy, but he is also a huge ****.   he loves to drop names, and talk about how he was involved in every major social movement since WWII.  He loves saying he knows important figures personally.  He is also EXTRELY lefty.
Peter & Will are the coolest teaching duo of all time.  Badasses!
Rutkoff and Scott are amazing Professors who jointly add flavor to an amazing class!
opinions as a class. fun and interesting, but he needs to leave kenyon.
Set in his ways, yet open to other viewpoints.  Immensely knowledgeable.
he's very interesting
No Comments
fun

What a guy.  One of Kenyon's great lecturers capable of weaving together a social-science tapestry that goes well-beyond boilerplate history.  France was never so interesting as when this man talks about it.

This man is a genius.  He has mastered the english language.  Half the time I didn't understand his words, but could always follow his structured and laid out lectures.  I learned more from him than any other professor I've ever had.  He alone made me love history.

I've taken 3 classes w/ Prof. Maguire.  He's excellent -- whether you're looking to fulfill your distribution requirements or are a budding history major, I'd recommend ANY of his classes highly (I've taken Modern Europe, Modern France, and Early Modern Europe w/ him).

Had him for IPHS and early modern europe. Seminar was great, and helpful at explaining difficult concepts. In lecture, gives precise and focused, but be prepared to take a lot of notes. Also, does a good job of trying to bring in discussion even in a lecture size class. Great, and smart prof, take a class with him if possible.
FANTASTIC professor.  Great lectures, always well-prepared, fair and consistent grader.

My most rewarding class. Maguire really pushes you to think beyond what you thought you could. YEA, he's awkward and spacey, always staring at some spot on the seminar table while he spits bullets of genius, but he generates mindblowing conversation. really inspirational, one of those teachers you never forget. I can't wait til he comes back
If/when he gets back to Kenyon, enroll in his classes, excellent professor for those who want to major in history or just are dabbling in a 100 level european history class.
Excellent lecturer.  Receives students well in office hours; helpful.  Grades fairly.
Rocks my world!  Sad because when I graduate, he will no longer rock my world.
Eloquent lectures, really nice, very passionate. Loved my history class beacuse of him.
Incredibly brilliant... and i want to have his children.

dont take him for seminar! has no problem lecturing about the same thing for 3 hrs each week. too boring

Ellen might be the kindest and most enthusiastic professor I've had at Kenyon. And that stuff about her treating male students worse is bananas.

Ellen's style doesn't gel with everyone--she's super enthusiastic and sometimes just a little too peppy for an early class, but she will really help you engage with the reading in an interesting way. She's so sweet and her tutorials for essays are indispensable, especially if you're a first-year and still getting used to academic English writing.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: class is pretty easy but made me not really like english and skeptical about whether or not i wanted to take more english classes

Wonderful professor, really got me excited about English and college in general. She's very enthusiastic about the books she assigns, so if you're only taking the class to fulfill a requirement you probably won't have fun--but if you actually want to delve deeply into the literature, Ellen is the perfect guide. I'd take any class she taught.
Highly invasive... Does not treat you like an adult. Makes everyone speak every single class, micromanages way too much.
Enthusiastic, kind, and knowledgeable prof.   So much help with writing! Favorite class so far.

Professor Mankoff is a huge fan of the opinions of Professor Mankoff, and if yours are even one step out of line she comes down hard on you. Ironically made me a better essay writer though because I'd disagree with her more often than not and thus had to prove everything flawlessly to get a decent grade.
Attitude is frustrating

Great professor.  Will shape up your writing a lot if you listen to her and go to office hours.  Her topics aren't always right up my street but she's enthusiastic and really friendly, so it's easy to appreciate the literature with her teaching it.

Mankoff definitely makes you a better writer, but is a very difficult grader. Reading quizzes focus on incredibly specific details and often her attitude is frustrating. There are many opportunities for extra help.

She'll make you work for every grade point but you'll come out a much better writer as well as a much deeper thinker. She forces you to examine the text in a different way and to pay strict attention to detail in your writing. Overall a great professor if you're looking for a challenge.

We love Ellen!  She's amazingly awesome!  She is extremely helpful when she gives comments on your writing.  Her enthusiasm spurs the enthusiasm of the class.  She is easily sidetracked, but really knowledgeable about a lot.  This class requires a huge amount of reading.

I adore this woman. Her specialty really wasn't my favorite and it's still not, but she made the works studied accessible and interesting. Moreover, her clear passion for not only the material but also for her students sets her apart from some of her colleagues. She's really in it for teaching stuff she loves, which is pretty cool.
nah. not so good. enthusiastic, has a funny laugh, but i don't recommend her.
Ellen is the sort of teacher who's at her best for the serious, interested student.
Hated Kenyon like I've hated few other places, but this teacher was pretty respectable.

My best English or any class at Kenyon so far.  Challenging and inspiring prof, also extemely helpful and friendly with advising even if she's not your advisor.  She improved my writing, and she loves teaching.
Ellen Mankoff is the pits. She doesn't come CLOSE to representing the Kenyon English department.
So nice and helpful! Always willing to help you with your papers. My writing definitely improved because of this class.

??? i was in the same class as previous rater and have NEVER found a prof more helpful with written work, going over drafts, etc.  yes she's demanding, but also generous, kind, patient (and modest).  learned a lot more than chaucer in this class.
Snide, very full of herself and her intellect. Grades papers harshly, not very helpful in office hours. Class left me with a bad taste in my mouth
Awesome Teacher

she is horrible, turned me off to the english major - a hard thing to do at kenyon. she's heavily biased, kind of endearing in her love for the literature, but takes it way overboard. she's mostly just mean and pathetic.
Great class.  Friendly helpful prof, in class and out.
great choice for intro, enthusiastic in class, helpful/generous in office hours, slow but THOROUGH grader
Very difficult and unfair grader.  Biased towards the students who see her in her office hours.
One of the most caring, helpful, friendly teachers I've had at Kenyon or anywhere.
She's very devoted to her class, really loves everything she teaches, and is unbelivably friendly. Take something with her if you possibly can, she's as Kenyonish as they come.
It's this kind of class and this kind of teacher I came to Kenyon for.  Makes you feel like a member of a very smart family.
Not suprising that she has devoted students--she's devoted to THEM.  Smart funny prof, and you couldn't ask for a better advisor.
obviously a few devoted students rallied after her previous terrible reviews. worst class i ever took at kenyon. boooooo. avoid like the plague.

Took two classes from her, and in retrospect, realize that I learned more from her Milton class than any other I took at Kenyon:  if she's teaching it, jump at the chance. Incredibly knowledgeable prof.
demanding but always willing to help.  Answers email as soon as you send it.
Very helpful, especially in office hours.  Really cares about students and material.  While she may take a bit of time to get used to, she is definitely worth it.
Really works hard with students on their writing.  Long books in this class but she makes them exciting.  I learned a lot and was never bored.
Challenging but worth it.  She taught me how to read and think.  Pays attention to writing and really cares about her students.  Class was always fun!
Fabulous.  Truly cares about the students.
extremely  detail oriented ...memorize your MLA handbook. she can quote it verbatim.

wears on long, dangly earring in one ear and a much smaller one on the other ear. these earings rotate ears periodically so one ear does not droop more than the other. she is a unique woman and has a good heart.
one of the finest professors at this college.  genuinely cares about her students and will go out of her way to help.
Can be lazy & favors females as a general rule.  Challenging though.

An unorganized mess of an instructor who too often brought outside problems and prejudices to class. the only good thing to be said is that i think she really cares about her students succeeding, but her good intentions fail to make her a good teacher.

She's very enthusiastic, which is great, and keeps the class involved.  She can be a little intimidating, though.  I don't find her that approachable.  And I think her dislike of the verb  to be  is weird.  that and the fact that her earrings dont match.
Bases grades largely on how many weak verbs papers contain. Crazed feminist.
heinous, gives girls better grades than guys for no apparent reason
Good teacher, open to all opinions, laughs a lot, but presses feminism heavily.
No Comments
Made the middle ages interesting.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES

comment: Professor Bowman gives incredible lectures that provide a lot of clarity on what was going on in the Middle Ages, and the topics and discussions are made even more captivating by his passion for the subject. The readings take a lot of time, but what you get out of the class is definitely worth it! 50% of your grade is from projects that you choose.

Lots to read, which, for me, was tough. However, most of the assigned readings are interesting enough. Bowman's lectures are enjoyable and while most classes consist of rather lengthy lectures, he also adds in some engaging activities. DO YOUR READINGS. You *may* be quizzed on them. There are pop quizzes.

While he assigns lots of reading (about 3-4 hours of it per class if you take notes), and while it's focused on an earlier time period than I was expecting (more Roman & Byzantine than the Dark Ages, though there are some vikings towards the end), Bowman makes up for it with his great personality and sense of humor. I have lots of respect for him.

Brilliant and funny, captivating lectures on (admittedly) dull topics. 200 pages of 6th century primary source reading per week is not unheard of. Class was difficult, but Bowman is a fair grader. Made the class interesting for everyone, even those who weren't interested originally. Highly recommended!
Most brilliant professor I have ever had.

An excellent lecturer, who presents information in an interesting way, and draws clear connections to topics previously covered. Works humor into lecturers. Provides helpful feedback on written assignments, and was a very fair grader. A kind, funny person.

Great guy!!! Material could have been more interesting, but I suppose that's to be expected with a middle ages history class. One of the best lecturing and funniest professors I've had at Kenyon. A fair grader.
very funny, extremely smart, he made the lectures fun and interesting. his slide shows were informative, and his comments on papers were helpful. the best professor I've had so far!!!

At first, it's hard to know what he expects from you, but as you get further into the semester you understand what he's looking for. Tough grader, very reading-intensive course, mostly primary sources. Very funny guy, encourages you to poke fun at the text but also recognize the importance. Sometimes class felt too long. LOTS OF READING.

gives a lot of reading, but i'm glad to say i read it and can add all of it to my library. the man is very cerebral and a tough grader, but he makes one want to work harder, achieve more. he's tough to read, but he has a good sense of humor and an asset to the history department
No Comments
A great lecturer, he demands a lot from you but if you actually put a little bit of effort into the class, he''s incredibly funny and nice.  This man can see through BS like anything: don't even try.
Great class, great professor!!
Great lecturer, but if you don't know your stuff or try to give a bs answer, he'll call you on it and poke fun at you.
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments
No Comments
he's really nice, but there's a ton of reading
great teacher. entertaining. interesting. A LOT of reading
smart, witty, and helpful professor

I don't think Read Baldwin has ever planned anything in his entire life. He is a nice man, but a wholly unorganized professor. He also offers the MOST UNHELPFUL feedback I have ever gotten. Additionally, he provides little to no instruction but has very specific expectations for the final product. In summary, just don't take a class with him.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Read is a nice man outside of class. In class, however, he is confusing and unclear about expectations, but has a very specific idea about what he wants. If you don't do something exactly the way he likes (even though he'll never tell you what it IS he likes), he'll grade harshly. Thank god I never have to take a class with him again.

As a typical arts class at Kenyon, this class is project heavy, and so it is a lot of work. However, Read is willing to work with you, your schedule, and your ideas. Even though this was an 8:10 class, I did not mind having to be up for it.
He is nice if you talk to him often and be friends with him. He is really strict with attendance! Take it if you think creating art is wroth getting up early for an 8:10 class.
the best

hands down one of the best professors at kenyon. although he is a fan of the abstract stuff, if you're persistent with your ideas you're fine. great personality, great heart. take all of his classes. do it.

If you are looking for a professor  who will graciously provide coffee and half & half and give you time and space to create, Read is the professor for you.  He certainly likes the color black, but has a good eye and is not unwilling to hear alternative opinions.  Much more fun than the average professor!

I had a great time in this class. I learned so much about art and drawing. I have never taken a drawing class and was intimidated in the beginning, but Read guided me through it and helped my true talent to flourish. He is one of the best professors I have had.
He was a ****bag sometimes.  Sometimes he's not.  He only sees things his way and can be tongue and cheek.

a great class if you are good at working on your own. read was definately there to help if asked, but usually just let us do our own thing. really into the colors red and black so if at a loss, just throw some of those into the mix and you're all set. he's also really quirky and kind of hot.
No Comments
he is awesome, and will help you with whatever you want to do (just ask!!).  The perfect type of art teacher since he lets you do whata you want with class time vs. out of class work.

His intro art class was the best art class I took at Kenyon (and I was an art major).  Maybe he seems biased toward abstract stuff, but the class is about 'color and design' so I'm not sure what else you'd expect.  He taught really great stuff and was a great teacher.
i didn't learn a thing, but had a great time.  just have a sense of humor about him, and you'll enjoy him more.
No Comments
No Comments

Tries to push students in a very particular direction: absract conceptual stuff. I wanted to learn to paint flowers and still lifes and  naked chicks but he made me do stupid stuff. Sometimes helpful when I had already though of a concept and was partway
No Comments
Biased opinion of art; makes you do abstract crap; would never give a clear answer on his reasons for poor grades in the class
No Comments
slide shows, strange color projects, famously long-winded conversations about nothing/art: fabulous.
confused, unclear, biased
good prof

A gem. He is incredibly knowledgeable and could (and sometimes does) talk endlessly on the subject at hand. Most days are standard lectures, but despite the subject of art being dry to some, I've found no problem in maintaining interest throughout classtime. Very caring and definitely deserves more people coming to office hours than he gets.
Very cool guy

Such a kind man with such a passion for architecture. I learned a lot of cool things and enjoyed the class, but the tests were almost al memorization and he made us do a graded drawing assignment at the beginning of the year, which felt a little unreasonable, because lots of people were taking art history because they couldn't do art.

Professor Dwyer is the reason people choose Kenyon.  He is very interested in his subject matter and the ideas of his students.  He is available and helpful to them and patient, as well.  To top it all off, he is just a really good natured, kind-spirited person.  Not an easy grader, however.

Art history may be the single most boring subject taught at institutions of higher learning in the United States. Dwyer is a really nice guy who did an adequate job teaching a subject that makes me want to blow my head off. You need to study a lot for the tests, unless you've got a great memory, but he's a fair grader.

We spent most of our time out of the classroom in archives and special collections.  Prof. Dwyer showed us how to describe and inventory works of art:  I now want to work in a museum or in an archive. Prof. Dwyer was all business  in the survey I took from him, in this course he was very enthusiastic and appreciative of student effort and interest.

I've had Prof. Dwyer a couple of times now and I have to say that he is a great professor. He is sincerely interested in his studies and enjoys teaching the subject matter. It is definitely worth taking one of his classes, especially an upper level.

I wish I had taken a class with Dwyer before the senior seminar.  He seems to know everything about art history, and is very helpful on an individual basis.  He demands a lot of his students, but is willing to provide clear guidance.

Dwyer's awesome.  He knows all that one could ever expect an Art History professor to know on ancient and medieval art.  His lectures are about as good as you're gonna get in Art History.  One of the funniest professors at Kenyon if you're pay close attention.

I took his architecture class. His lectures are often dry however he is a very intelligent man. The tests are very hard and there is a lot of memorization from lists. However, I did learn a lot. The class is what you make of it; motivation and an interest in architecture are key.
One of the best and most endearing profs at Kenyon.  Very helpful and well informed, a true scholar, and an excellent teacher.
Lots of material covered in a thorough manner.  Tests not easy but you learn a lot.
Great hands-on class with a truly scholarly prof.  Interested in just about everything, and goes out of his way to help students.
This man knows everything!  so smart and one of the nicest professors at kenyon.
WOW his tests are IMPOSSIBLE! Lots and lots of memorization. Making tons of flashcards doesn't really help. Other than that Professor Dwyer is such a sweetheart! Very intelligent and interesting man.
very dear man, takes us on trips.  knows everything!  a true scholar.
He is very dry/boring in a topic that can be oh so exciting!  I ended up feeling sorry for him because he had trouble controling the class.  I can appreciate his intelligence though.
Incredibly kind and helpful. He also knows just about everything.
Can seem dry but oh so brilliant.  Very helpful one on one, in survey and seminar.
very boring, not a great grader.  easy tests
Tries really hard.  I feel kind of sorry for him, but his lectures are just really really dry.  But then again, it is architecture.
Incredibly knowledgable, willing to go out of his way to help students individually.  Highly recommend.
Wonderful!  I learned so much.
I Love architecture and he knows a lot about it, but his teaching style is very boring.
Yes Eugene can be dry but he is kind, knowledgable and very helpful.  Visit him during office hours and he comes to life--much better 1 on 1.  Goes out of his way for his students.
Not exciting but very knowledgable and nice.  Like a brilliant grandpa.
He knows his stuff but doesn't make it very interesting for the students
No Comments
I've had heithaus for two courses, and about to have him for a third...he is a great teacher who provides all the information and tools necessary to succeed in class. he's also a really nice guy!
Interesting class.  Easy tests.  Boring to listen to but overall not bad.  Take the class.
Great

Ray was nice enough, but he is the sole reason I left the bio department.  definitely plays favorites (more than any prof i had at kenyon). isn't wildly fascinating, either.  left me a little more disappointed with biology than i would have thought possible.  :(
Ray is great. He's a very relaxed and nie person. Teaches from power point, which can be boring, but he's pretty clear about what he expects. An easy grader.
He's a very nice guy and SUPER helpful. Very approachable and passionate about bio.
Boring but nice about turning homework in late.  I don't think he knows me by my face if that gives you an idea about the class.
Not very engaging. Knows no one cares, and his style reflects it. Grades arbitrarily. Wears a whale belt buckle. YOU decide.
a bigger bio dork was never born. do the readings and enjoy his fun anecdotes... don't worry about falling asleep during boring powerpoints.
